Check out our latest vlog, link in bio :)', 'How was your July?', 'Reunited!', 'The finest pussy I seen all year', "Today is one of the most important days of my life.

1. We spent 10 days shooting and 2 weeks editing around the clock for what I believe to be the best client I ever worked with, producing 2 videos that I have never been prouder to show. Yes, I would say it's the best video I ever made (and I've made A LOT of videos). I edited over 3000+ videos over the last decade.

2. I would like to thank @klooksg for being the coolest client ever for taking the leap of faith with us even though we have no subscribers or followers. It is also the first time in my life as an editor that I had no changes to make.

3. I would like to thank my crew for toughing it out and working around the clock to make this happen. Especially @whitexsmoke for crashing on my sofa and working around the clock with me to deliver this video, and @bombiibii for putting up with my shit and whining and still trying to make the best of shituations

4. I would like to thank my girlfriend, @cherylenechan for taking care of me and making sure I didn't collapse on the table while editing and forgetting to go to the toilet or eat.

5. Last but not least, I would like to thank what little friends and fans I had left for sharing and supporting the video and supporting my comeback. It hasn't been easy, but as I mentioned before, all I ever wanted to do was make good videos with no drama, no shade, no tea, and no politics. That will be the direction of my new channel. We also won't be releasing videos on a schedule because I do wish for work-life balance. 

Let our work speak for us.

Link in bio

As long as I am fit enough to get my $500 from annual IPPT, anything else would be a plus ☺️', 'Just finished reading The Subtle Art of Not Giving A F*ck, and if there’s one thing I’ve taken away from the book it’s the idea of embracing uncertainty in your life.

‘The more you try to be certain about something, the more uncertain and insecure you will feel.’

Seeking to control outcomes for things (relationships, getting accepted for that job) that are outside of our control would bring anxiety and impatience. It’s easy to look at something not going your way, and then let your anxiety create these crazy implausible branching narratives to believe the certainty of something not going your way.

This is because of a tendency to interpret your experience in a way that coheres to your previous experiences, feelings and beliefs. In the midst of that, it would be easy to fill the plot holes with our own narratives just to make it seem like everything makes sense and is rational. It’s something I definitely used to succumb to, and some semblance of that pattern of activity still remains.

‘The more you embrace being uncertain and not knowing, the more comfortable you will feel in knowing what you don’t know.’

Perhaps the best thing to do in times of uncertainty would be to simply… hang loose 🤙🏻', 'Back in the Jurassic era, I used to only wear black and white. I am proud to announce that I actually wear colours now. I like this shirt colour.

@xingweird helped me take this pic', 'Year 3 for me in NUS was an extremely tough time. I was riddled with anxiety, stemming from a failing relationship, worrying about a lack of direction of what I wanted to do (aka quarter-life crisis), felt like an imposter in the course I was in, and academic burnout (Computer Science is tough).

Up till that point I never really associated the idea of mental wellbeing with myself. Me, with mental health issues? No way. Only people that were clinically diagnosed could claim they had those issues. Well, that was what I thought.

Intense worry about the uncertainty of my future, feeling a sense of overwhelm and lack of control in my life due to school, constant fatigue and having trouble concentrating. A feeling of dread when it came to nighttime as I struggled to sleep; my head clogged up with thoughts and worries that plagued me throughout the day. These are all symptoms of general anxiety disorder.

You see my fellow students, you aren’t as alone as you think you are. We are all one and the same in our feelings, even if our problems differ. You may think that the problem of you stressing to get an assignment done on time is inferior to that of someone else going through a heartbreak, thus invalidating your right to be anxious.

But it’s not a competition of who has the biggest problem, where only the ones facing the most have the right to seek help for their mental health. All of us have our own problems. The right to your own feelings lies within yourself. It would be great if we could collectively start to acknowledge our own mental wellbeing, to realise that it’s okay that we might have issues, and also to know that we aren’t alone.

To help with that, NUS is organising K(NO)W Stigma 2022, an event centred around breaking the stigmas around mental wellness. Join them in a panel discussion that would help demystify the topic of mental wellness, as well as create a safe space for more in-depth dialogue surrounding mental health.

For more details, head to the @nus.hwb Instagram or Facebook page, and you can sign-up for the event through the link in my bio.

#NUSAreuOK #NUSKnowStigma2022', "Goodbye Sheares Hall, the place I could call a home for the past academic year.

A lesson I've learned about home: A dream home doesn't have to be a bungalow filled with swimming pools, bowling alleys, and more amenities than one could need. You don't need a penthouse, 10,000 square feet, or a balcony that stretches out far and wide. A home is a lot more than the superficial. It's a place of safety, security, comfort, and peace. A place you go to at the end of an exhausting day and immediately feel relaxed. A place without judgment, and where you can let your mind rest and be at ease. Even if that's a small little room at the corner of NUS.

I'm not someone that has a large amount of attachment to Sheares Hall as compared to some of my other graduating schoolmates. I didn't join many events or CCAs, nor have I really made a lot of friends that would honestly persist past this graduation from the hall. But I would be lying if I said that 3 of the 4 years I've stayed here haven't impacted me in a large way.

There are a few things I would miss. The peaceful and quiet nature of Pasir Panjang. Communal living with the few close friends I've taken away. The subtle chirping of birds nestled on the roof (although I won't miss the bird poop), and the gentle breeze that flows through the corridor of the rooftop floor that I stayed on. The idea of having the beautiful campus of NUS like my own backyard. The low-rise buildings nestled around the area, giving me an unobstructed view of the sky in its entirety. As you can tell, this allowed me to experience some magnificent sunsets over the past 10 months.

But what I will miss the most would be having this space I could call mine, even if it was just for a short 10 months. A place I could feel safe in, a space where I could do anything I wanted. A small little room where I could feel at peace. At home. And if this is a teaser of what owning my own place feels like, consider me motivated in wanting to achieve that sooner rather than later.

Goodbye Sheares. Thank you for the lessons learned, the people I've met, the tranquility you've given me, and the motivation you've sparked inside of me.", 'petition for power pose emoji', "Senior's farewell night in Sheares Hall, time for another WADIO

Photo by James Reynolds', 'I can’t believe I get to work with Aaron Dessner. When Aaron came into my life, I was ushered into his world of free-flowing creativity where you don’t overthink, you just make music. His generosity of spirit and humility bleeds into every part of his life, and that’s why so many artists have jumped at the chance to be a part of his collaborative project, Big Red Machine. A song we wrote (which also features ⚡️Justin Vernon✨) is out today! It’s called Renegade. Thanks Aaron for asking me to show up at your party.', 'I’ve always said that the world is a different place for the heartbroken. It moves on a different axis, at a different speed. Time skips backwards and forwards fleetingly. The heartbroken might go through thousands of micro-emotions a day trying to figure out how to get through it without picking up the phone to hear that old familiar voice. In the land of heartbreak, moments of strength, independence, and devil-may-care rebellion are intricately woven together with grief, paralyzing vulnerability and hopelessness. Imagining your future might always take you on a detour back to the past. And this is all to say, that the next album I’ll be releasing is my version of Red.
 
Musically and lyrically, Red resembled a heartbroken person. It was all over the place, a fractured mosaic of feelings that somehow all fit together in the end. Happy, free, confused, lonely, devastated, euphoric, wild, and tortured by memories past. Like trying on pieces of a new life, I went into the studio and experimented with different sounds and collaborators. And I’m not sure if it was pouring my thoughts into this album, hearing thousands of your voices sing the lyrics back to me in passionate solidarity, or if it was simply time, but something was healed along the way.

Sometimes you need to talk it over (over and over and over) for it to ever really be... over. Like your friend who calls you in the middle of the night going on and on about their ex, I just couldn’t stop writing. This will be the first time you hear all 30 songs that were meant to go on Red. And hey, one of them is even ten minutes long.

Red (Taylor’s Version) will be out November 12.

@flanneryunderwood 📸', 'Really enjoyed and appreciate sitting down with my friend @thattracysmith & @cbssundaymorning ☀️ 

We chopped up a lot of meaningful topics - including running for POTUS. 

With midterms here and a presidential election 2 years away, I’ve been approached by the most influential in politics on both sides of the aisle asking and supporting that I run for President. 

It’s a humbling, grateful and inspiring feeling to even have these conversations, as I’m not a politician nor have I ever aspired to be one. 

But I am a patriot to my core, love my country and everyone in it. 

But being a father to my little girls is the most important thing in my life. To raise ‘em and always be there, during these critical years in their life. 
I know what it’s like to not be there all the time as a father, because of an unrelenting work schedule. 
I won’t let that happen ever again. 

Choosing parenting over presidency. 

Hope you guys enjoy our interview tomorrow on CBS Sunday Morning ☀️

#Go和一億人一起去冒險', 'Hi Mom!', 'Embark on a mission with our Founding Members' collection - ARC Stellars!

Let's make ourselves heard on a global scale! ✨ It's time for Asia Web3 space to make our mark in NFT history.

#IntoTheARC #AsiaTogetherStrong

ARC Stellars is a collection of 1,688 priced at 3ETH each so that we can onboard a curated group of people to help co-build ARC 💜. The artwork is unique to this Founding Members' collection!

This is a 100% invite-only mint. 1,500 are for Friends of ARC and Pyxis holders who have been allowlisted and invited to mint. 188 will be reserved in ARC’s Treasury for marketing purposes and community initiatives.

1,688 is the MAXIMUM THRESHOLD we are willing to allow as we accounted for factors like user experience on the ARC app. Our bigger goal is to make sure we curate a strong and engaged base community of founding members.

ARC Stellar holders (who also hold Pyxis) will also get ✨a free mint ✨ of our first co-created NFT project!

You can only mint ARC Stellars if you are allowlisted and invited to mint. You will receive an invitation via email. You are more likely to be invited if:

🟢 You have demonstrated that you'll be able to bring value through the pooling of your resources, ideas, skill sets and networks with the ARC community OR

🟢 You have participated in our BYFOB programme OR

🟢 You are an active contributor to the community. You can contribute by writing content and threads that add value to ARC, being active on our socials and Discord, being an advocate for ARC’s community IRL and online.

While minting Pyxis early will be one of the considerations, the 3 points above will play a bigger role in improving your odds (demonstrating value, referring like-minded individuals and contributing).

JD', 'Two months before the world was subjected to the shocking live coverage of the merciless, bloodthirsty and public daylight murder of JFK in Nov. 1963, Bob Dylan sat down to write a song‚Ä¶ He had a particular idea in mind, which he recorded mere weeks before Kennedy‚Äôs tragic Assassination. Dylan had already achieved stratospheric acclaim from his treasure-producing workmanship and poetic abilities. He had already jacked up the bar of songwriting to an untouchable level. He also became a reluctant prophet, which can be quite an occupational hazard‚Ä¶Yet he remained himself while dodging all manner of con artists, bloodsuckers, angles, arrows, ignorance, injustices, and scrutinization of his life. His intentions remained pure. So he sat down and wrote the gold standard of protest songs, the seminal and most significant, mind boggling and staggeringly poetic, prophetic protest song the world will ever know: ‚ÄúThe Times They Are A-Changin‚Äô‚Äù. Dylan‚Äôs song applies to Covid-19, it also, very strongly applies to the life altering image of George Floyd, forever seared to our brains‚Ä¶ For me, it applies to the moment we are in, it applies to the moment they were in in 1963, it applies to everything before and everything since and everything that will be. 
I chose to perform this song live, for my friend @drbarbarasturm Covid benefit several weeks ago‚Ä¶ I didn‚Äôt really know how to play it, but I figured I‚Äôd give it a shot, as it seemed to apply so well. And it applies now, more than ever. It was performed a couple of weeks before our collective paralysis was rendered complete by the images of our fellow human George Floyd being cruelly and brutally tortured to death on live TV.

Let us take a moment to remember the sacrificial hero George Floyd and look with hope towards the changes that his tragic death will cause. And let‚Äôs salute the reluctant prophet Bob Dylan and the dream of change he inspired then, now, and onwards‚Ä¶ His impact is that of Shakespeare, Marlowe, Hunter Thompson, Marlon Brando, Woody Guthrie, William Blake, Picasso, Bach and Mozart. 
Dylan‚Äôs song is to be kept near you, AT ALL TIMES!!! All love and respect,
JD', 'As the majority of American people, our global community and our extended family of humans helplessly watched a man die on television‚Ä¶ I too, was exposed to the atrocity of blatant barbarism, \xa0ruthless cruelty and unmitigated lack of humanity. \xa0A handcuffed man, pleading for his life lay prone with the full weight of a man sworn to defend the peace on his neck. The victim of this heinous act of cowardice, George Floyd, told the officers that he could not breathe. As he called for his dead mother, how could our collective hearts not break as his face was ground and mashed firmly into the pavement by those sworn to protect him, and all of us? Justice, I desperately hope, will address the horror of Officer Chauvin‚Äôs nonchalance and indifference to his participation in the agony, suffering and ultimately the murder of our fellow traveler George Floyd in a grotesque illustration of the abuse of power!!!
There is no way to make sense of what is senseless. There is no way to restore a life that has been taken. Just as there is no way to un-break a heart that is broken. 
What we can do is make a vow to ourselves that racism and the ignorance inherent in such judgmental ugliness that it gives birth to, is NO LONGER AN OPTION!!! THERE MUST BE A CHANGE!!! DEMAND IT!!!! My dear friend and brother, Killer Mike - (Run The Jewels), is a brilliant musician, artist, activist for social justice and the son of an Atlanta Policeman. He is also, one of the kindest, most caring and loving human beings that I‚Äôve ever had the pleasure and honor to know!!! I beg everyone to listen to the remarks of this true statesman. True statesmen have never been so needed, and they‚Äôve never been in such short supply. 
With All Love, 
JD', 'It‚Äôs odd, the things that we once gave such pure, intense focus and devotion to for months on end. Then suddenly the wind shifts and off we go on a new tack. And for far too long, these earlier interests or passions sadly fall by the wayside and recede into the vast recesses of some hoarder‚Äôs crawlspace in the brain cloaked in heaps of the other things that my skull had no room for‚Ä¶until recently. 
I found this painting, which I had started in 2006 ‚Ä¶ for 14 years I‚Äôd never touched the painting ‚Äì the occasional glance, at best. Yet it somehow always lingered in my mind, this piece of unfinished business. 
Even while we are forced to live in the immediate, some strange species of the interrupted passion that has been invested in an object we once focused on awaits our return from far away. I will keep you apprised of the progress! All Love,

I know what youre thinking 🤔 

"Danny isn't this cheating? Surely 4 colas means 4 separate videos" 

My answer is 🤫 

"Yup it should be, but I dont give a damn cos I make these videos and rules are meant to be broken" 

#rebelwithacause #breakingmyownrules #iwantedtofinishon25episodes #anyonelesegotocdwithnumberslikethat?

#pradabeautypartner", None, "I didn’t actually set out to start making films. I’d say the real beginning was taking in what I saw going on around me on set, & then starting to learn how to apply it in other parts of my life. For instance: my Mum nervously would be getting ready for her job interviews, & knowing I knew how to apply makeup after so many hours of watching other people do it in the makeup chair, we made it our ritual that I would do her face before any of her important occasions. 
Then filmmaking itself started by making love letters to my friends. Whether it was styling them, or producing photoshoots for their websites or headshots for their businesses - I loved helping out. Selfishly sometimes I also did it because I just wanted them to see all the beauty I saw in them that they never seemed to get. 
Then over time I started assisting a friend running sound on set. Then, very slowly I started working behind the camera (It hurt my back so much at first 😂). Then I got involved in editing. Now here I am, sharing my first go at directing something. 
I couldn’t have done it without the friends I could be vulnerable enough with to show that I didn’t know what I was doing & to ask for help from every step of the way. To these people (you know who you are) you have literally made a mark on my life & I hope I always get to make things WITH you. Thanks for believing in me. 
@emma_webstah this is my love letter to you. As a woman I always found the idea of living alone terrifying… & when you told me you had been living in the garage above your studio to dedicate yourself to what you really wanted to do despite everyone’s “good and well intentioned advice” - was when I knew I wanted to make my first tiny film about you. I just instantly wanted to try & capture who you were & the importance of your work. That's what feels so beautiful about directing to me - you get to fall in love!
Thanks for being so cool Emma. Your work, writing & being inspires me so much. I feel so grateful to have friends like you that I just hope I can keep up with courage-wise. Thanks for being as excited as I was about cookie dough for lunch on the shoot day. And you rock that jumpsuit. E

너무 생각이 많은 밤이라 다 적을 순 없지만… 지금은 진짜 나에게 집중해야 할때.. 너무 오랜시간 마음에 병으로 나를 놓아버려 왔기에.. 이제는 나는 기필코 일어서야만 한다. 어떠한 장애물이 오더라도 난 견뎌낼꺼다. 난 할 수 있다. 

난 더이상 혼자가 아니니까 
이제는 나와 ‘함께’ 하는 분들을 위해 
맞서 싸우고 이겨낼테야!!

아직도 생생히 기억나는 뮤지컬배우 건명오빠가 무대위에서 날 소개해 주셨던 그날.. “배우 박선영” 이라는 말 한마디가 무대에 서는 것을 포기하지 않고 뮤지컬 배우로 성장할 수 있게 해준 큰 힘이 되었다. 무엇보다 정말 존경하는 선배님께서 데뷔 10년 만에 나에게 배우라는 말을 처음 해준 분이었기에 더 의미있고 감사했다.. 나는 가수고 배우다. 
그건 변함이 없는데 참 시작이 아이돌이었기에 모든 것이 순탄치 않았다. ‘편견’을 깨버리기엔 난 너무 어렸고 부족했다. 그건 편견이 아니라 사실이었을 수 있기에,,나는 그들에 기준에 맞게 더 노력하고 더 잘하고 더 완벽해야 했으며 강해져야 했다. 이제는 누군가에 인정보다는 내가 나를 인정하고 싶다. 

난 항상 나를 엄청나게 사랑하고 인정할 만큼 최선을 다하는 사람이었는데.. 아이돌 생활하면서 참 남에게 인정받고 싶어서 죽도록 노력했던 것 같다.. 이젠 그렇게 안살아야지.

쉼 없이 달려왔던 아이돌시절, 참 바보같을 정도로 열심히 살아왔던 나의 10대 기억은 지하연습실과 참치김밥, 그리고 눈물이다. 너무 아파서 누구에게도 꺼내지 않았었는데, 이제는 말 할수 있을 것 같다. “그래도 나 한번 사는 인생 열심히 최선을 다했다!” 라고 .. 이제는 더 용기내어 하고자 하는 음악을 하고싶다. 그리고 나는 내 목소리를 사랑하게 해준 귀한작품을 만났다. Thank you. @thehelenpark 💜 

KPOP Broadway reignited the hidden passion inside of me. 

In retrospect, I barely stopped. I kept grinding, practicing, and doing whatever I can so that I could “keep going.” Much so, that my teenage memories consist of underground practice rooms, kimbap, and tears. I kept most of this by myself, but just wanted to express my gratitude to everyone at KPOP for making me able to believe.

Also, I am a day late!:-( 

Not many people know what autism is, or what this entails, but to those who care, thank you.

HH (my brother) was diagnosed with autism at age 2. This was a huge blow to my family. My parents questioned: Why HH of all people? Why us? This is the case for most families whose kids are diagnosed with autism. 

Given that Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD) was not well known 21 years ago as it is today, we worried about my brother’s development and ability to integrate into society. A society that wasn’t forgiving, or accepting to those who did not seem “normal” ( for a lack of a better word ). Everyday, we worried about how HH was going to go to school; make friends; get a job; talk to people; be self sufficient: and the list goes on. The worries were endless. How could we cope with having a family member with ASD, when we ourselves didn’t even know what ASD was? So, what is ASD?

ASD is a developmental disability that affects 1 in 150 children in 🇸🇬, and it is generally seen as a different way of thinking. People with Autism often have problems with emotional, social and communication skills- which is why many people think of them as “weird”, “loner”, “eccentric”. 

But people with autism should not be defined solely by how they communicate, feel, or act. They just operate a little differently, and different is not necessarily bad. Different can be good. But not everyone thinks that way! And that begets the question: how can I be more accepting of someone who has autism? 

I don’t think there is a right answer to this. You can find a way to do so that suits you! It will definitely not be easy, but please remember to be respectful, and get over prejudice & bias that you may have. It is not everyday you may meet someone with autism, but when you do, be kind. 

It has taken me & my family years, to learn how to cope and function with HH. The journey was difficult, and I do not think it will be easy for years to come. But I am grateful for everything HH has taught us- to be kind, patient, and loving.

渾身の力作です。
個人的に今までにないサウンドをトライできたり、
実はイントロをうたってるのは俺で、自分の作品に初めて自分の声入れてみてたり、
新しいことにフレッシュに挑戦できた曲。
創作と向き合うことや思い通りにいかないことをbrb.が詩にしてくれました。
たくさん聴いてくれ🔥
-Shin Sakiura

From the get go, we had all decided to explore a new sound together, much of it being inspired by Shin's amazing track.
We wanted the lyrics to channel the rebellious, road trip-vibe within the music; the ‘wild child’ in the song represents someone that’s anything but careful, a risk taker and with that a realization that going out of your comfort zone can be a good thing sometimes.
The song is about letting go, and just having a good time - we hope that "WILD CHILD" inspires you to do the same!

['I’m my own biggest critic and the loudest voice in my head. The voice that’s constantly telling myself that I’m never going to ever achieve enough or never going to reach my goals because I’m too unfocused, I’m too loud, I moved too quickly and recklessly.

But I almost always forget that little voice in my head that’s constantly reassuring me that I’m doing amazing, I have all the tools I need to succeed and I really just need to breathe. I constantly felt locked in a box but was holding onto the exact key that would set me free. This audio captured my exact thoughts these few days where I’m practicing to be more in touch with my feminine 💅🏼energy and to really find a balance between being hard on myself for the RIGHT reasons and rewarding myself for the steps I’ve made to get there. If this audio also resonated with you - drop me a ☀️ to share that it did! 💘', "Hi, i know I haven’t been posting much regarding mental health but today is International Women’s Day where it is a day that celebrates the progress made towards achieving gender equality and women's empowerment.

I thought - what better way to commemorate this day other than sharing a story of how I almost lost my life and lost a part of me last year and that this year, I’m taking back my power by not hiding behind the guilt, trauma and pain anymore.

TW: Ectopic Pregnancy, Death:

Early last year in January 2021, I rushed myself to the A&E at a hospital near my home because I thought I had appendicitis/ Rhabdomyolysis due to sharp pains in my abdomen. It turned out that I was pregnant and that it was an ectopic pregnancy, this occurs when a fertilized egg implants and grows outside the main cavity of the uterus (in my case it was on my left Fallopian tube). An ectopic pregnancy is also fatal for the fetus as it cannot survive outside of the uterus.

What this meant for me was that the pain I felt earlier in that day was all me - 5-6 weeks pregnant with a deceased fetus and with 700mls of blood flowing in my organs causing my internal bleeding from within. I was then rushed to surgery shortly after and was discharged 2 days later. 

I’ve lived with this pain everyday since then and I’ve went through a roller coaster of emotions, from pure denial that something this traumatic can ever happen to me, to dealing with the hospital debt after and trying to go back and forth to negotiate the instalments and lastly, to putting up a front to everyone I knew and hiding this truth for the longest time.

I’ve learned along the way that my toxic trait was thinking I could hold the world’s worries on my shoulders, and run. But all I was doing was trudging in mud that sank deeper each time. I’m done hiding behind my pain now, I’m still learning to let the people I’m closest to nearer to me but it’s still a work in progress.

But most of all, I’ve learned to take the power back, take charge of the narrative and I’ve learnt to appreciate my body and everything it does for me. We’re all a work in progress and just like so many others, I’m working each and every day towards a better version of myself. I’ve come to recognise not all days are great and to take the wins as we go! 🏆

today (yesterday) also marks just over a month following the death of a dude who was quintessential to this space.

no amount of consolation, catharsis, coping, vice, distraction, art, sappy songs, poetry, memorial, or pretty quotes about death can ever erase the tragedy and injustice of the loss of the boy with the kindest heart and the kindest smile, who deserved so much better from the world and the people in it. 

the essence of the surreal is something familiar in an unfamiliar context. it was beyond surreal to see a familiar body— one we know, we’ve touched, we’ve seen move, we love— lying in a casket wearing unfamiliar clothes (a suit he would have protested), with an unfamiliar hairstyle (he also would’ve protested), and a very unfamiliar wound just above the ear. a wound I can’t get out of my head. 

there is something so surreal about loving someone that does not exist (particularly when they existed just a few moments ago).

there is something so fundamentally wrong with sending a friend’s body into a furnace to burn. 

and now I realise how closely tied we are to spaces, whatever those spaces may be. because as time goes by, finn’s absence from all these spaces— figuratively (our group) and literally (this studio)— becomes increasingly clear and increasingly painful.

there is something so wrong with his absence from this world. and there is something so irreconcilable about his non-existence.

but as I grieve his death (and mourn a future that never will be), I also know I have no choice but to simultaneously celebrate his life, particularly on a day like today. and so we try and drink to him and remember good times, his laugh, his person, and his friendship. we pour whiskey at his memorial, and we keep a space open for him. we buy an extra beer. we remember what a fucking good person he was, and we try to let that goodness live through us. it doesn’t bring him back and nothing can ever be the same, but it’s the most we can do to preserve him. 

anyway, man would’ve turned 22 today. so ig happy birthday, finn. I miss you. I really, really hope you’re living it up at some kind of afterparty lol. somewhere.', '(1/2)

However, the true cause of our feelings is within us. For example, imagine yourself as a glass of water. Now, imagine past negative experiences as sediment at the bottom of your glass. Next, think of others as spoons. When one stirs, the sediment clouds your water. It may appear that the spoon caused the water to cloud - but if there were no sediment, the water would remain clear no matter what. The key, then, is to identify our sediment and actively work to remove it" -Josei Toda

Since moving to 🇺🇸, I forgot about Chuseok holiday I used to celebrate in Korea. It’s time for families to gather and give thanks for all the food they can share with each other. Not only we share good food but we also share laughter and remember our ancestors. 
This time around I feel fortunate to visit my grandparents’ graves and introduce @itsgahi to them. I always felt I want to pay my respect to them and I finally got a chance to do that this Chuseok. We also visited my 외할머니 and spent time with her. I would see my 외할머니 maybe every couple years and it’s good to be able to visit her on holidays like this. Then I visited my in-laws to share more good food and laughter. As I’m spending more time with them, I start to feel a bit more comfortable around them which is good. 
My first Chuseok was a bit busy but I think it’s awesome to make up for all the times I missed. The long distance was starting to wear on us and a poison started to fill my heart. Poison of resentment and hae started to penetrate deep into my heart and I was hating everything. I hated that Chloe’s not here, I hated that I experienced imperfect Singapore with the pandemic and I hated that my life felt incomplete all of sudden. And all that hate and blame was directed at Singapore for the rules and laws that prevented chloe and me being together on this island. I think me leaving this beautiful island is starting to show with resentment towards the country I live in and the place I work at.
But today my heart got convicted. I got convicted with the truth that I am loved. I am adored and I am looked after even if I don’t feel that. All of sudden I saw that how loved I am by people in Singapore. Yes, it’s sad that I am leaving this island and yes it’s stupid that it has come to this. However like the pastor Chris said today God’s grace and favour might dress differently for you than it does for other people. There is a reason God’s grace and favour is showing like this. And that God’s blessing is right in my face everyday. One of God’s blessings, my dear friend jonty, I processed that I am resenting Singapore but how foolish I was not to see how much I am loved by many people here. God specifically placed these people in my life for a reason and this circle I have in Singapore it’s not the end. It’s not permanent. I think maybe I was getting heart broken because I was secretly processing to “close” this chapter and closing meaning never see them again but that’s not true. It’s not permanent. I will see them again and I will be back again. This family is here to stay in my life and it might not be what I imagined to be but God’s grace is that much bigger, much bigger than what I can understand. ['DREAMS REALLY DO COME TRUE
——————
To be honest, I’m still in shock…
I’ve wished of this moment for years.
The donning of the whitecoat was my solace of inspiration, the pinnacle of my goals. 
I fondly remember watching the ceremonies of years past, often getting emotional.. as unbelievably cliche as it sounds. 
But to my fellow med hopefuls, I guess we relate to it somehow. 
——————
As I receive my whitecoat today, I can’t help but feel a pouring elation.
Not for the presence of excitement, but for the sobering weight of the profession.
We are now ‘medical students’, ‘doctors in training’, ‘people of responsibility’…
Gone are the days of hoping to be one, we are one, and we are treated as one. 
——————
With this thought and open eyes, I look forward to the next 5 years.
To the knowledge I seek, the people I’ll meet, the person I’ll be.
To everyone that has supported me, I try to be fancy with words, but for this my vocab is weak. 
Thank you is all I can speak.
——————
To the class of 2027, it’s gonna be a wild ride. I’m so lucky that it’s gonna be with y’all..
For it’s time to ‘show ourselves into the unknown’. :)', '~emo artist vibes ✅~

•
5.91mi total
39:58 chip time
31st/47 men’s 
•
My first @orchardstreetrunners race ever! If you don’t know about unsanctioned racing, this is where it’s at!
•
I had 2 things in mind going into the race: Study the course & Run on effort. When you race on the streets of Brooklyn and NYC you better be in control and know what your doing! 
•
Mile 1 - 6:09min/mi
The start line was In the heart of DUMBO with Manhattan Bridge as the back drop. Cutting through construction and parking lots. 

Mile 2 - 6:32min/mi
This was the start to my approach to cut through the Navy Yards ⚓️ Knowing I had to put in a small surge to blow through security and quickly get in and out of this industrial park. 

Mile 3 - 7:28min/mi
This was a tough effort! Basically a big hill out of the Navy Yards, the. A straight climb up Williamsburg Bridge. 
I’ve also been struggling with my breathing lately, so I definitely felt a small side stitch coming on again…

Mile 4 - 6:35min/mi
With the downhill of the bridge I was able to make up some time. I missed the first light off the bridge and had to take a small detour, which threw my bearings off and took me in a slightly wrong direction. 

Mile 5 - 7:42min/mi
I was lost in Chinatown for 2 blocks, which cost me about a minute and added 0.1mi to my route. Another runner was extremely lost and I was able to quickly navigate us back to the Manhattan Bridge, which meant another big climb for about half a mile. (If you’ve never ran in the city, your main elevation gain will come from the bridges 🌉) 

Finish (5.91mi) - 6:11min/mi
Coming off the bridge I was able to build a strong finish. Bringing the pace to around 5:05min/mi. The traffic lights were all in my favor and I was able to sprint up 5 blocks to the finish 🏁

Please Share & Follow ✅ for more run ideas‼️
•
I’m not going to lie, with a majority of my miles at “EASY” pace, it can get pretty mundane. 
Here’s one thing I try on some of my easy day runs ⤵️
FINDING A PACE FOR MY EASY DAY, AND PACING EXACTLY TO IT!
•
Here are a few ways to go about it:
First, look back at some of your recent Easy Day runs to figure out the average pace, then add about 10-15 seconds per mile as a guideline. (Remember “easy” is still an effort. So if it feels hard it’s okay to pull it back)

1️⃣ Start the run VERY conservative and slowly pick up the pace. This is called a Progressive Run, and those Easy Runs are a great way to practice! Try hitting your easy day goal pace as the overall average. 

2️⃣ Try to hit every split (mile or km) exactly at the planned pace. This is called Even Splits. This is usually best done on flatter terrain but it’s a great way to practice controlling your pace. 

3️⃣ Use your goal pace as a guideline, hide your watch and run based off effort. You might not end up exactly at the average pace you planned for, but this is a great way to practice road racing. Especially on hilly terrains. You learn to control your pace based on perceived effort!
•
Let me know on the comments if you’ve ever tried any of these! 💬

•
Let me know in the comments 💬
•
For context I am running at 6.0mph on the treadmill and the clip is about 10 seconds. 
[answer at the bottom ⬇️]
•
Cadence in running is defined by the amount of steps you take per minute. It’s also a part of the equation for running Pace
CADENCE + STRIDE LENGTH = RUN SPEED
•
Cadence is also often associated with running form. Usually a higher cadence between 170-190 steps per minute is used as a guideline in preventing over-striding. 
Please remember that each runner is built differently so the Steps Per Minute will vary and should not be used as a benchmark but more as a GUIDELINE.
•
ANSWER: ~180 steps per minute

6.21mi @ 6:47min/mi
Chip Time 42:07.12
204 of 3997
63F, cloudy ☁️ 
•
This was not the outcome I was aiming for. Target was a sub 40min 10km but just wasn’t able deliver. 

Mile 1 - 5:54min/mi
This course starts off quick downhill and planned to stay controlled, expecting a sub 6 first mile. 

Mile 2 - 6:54min/mi
The quarter mile leading to mile 2 is a massive hill dropping my pace to around a 9:00min/mi pace. My rushed warmup started to really show and caused my breathing to feel labored already. 

Miles 3,4,5 - 7:30, 7:07, 7:03min/mi
A massive side stitch at 2.5 miles just took me out! I had to stop 3 times and took the next 2.5 miles to recover ☠️ 
My mind just told me to quit at this point. I knew my PR attempt was not possible and honestly wanted to just rip the bib off and walk to the finish. The planned splits for this section of the course were: 6:20, 6:05, 6:35

Mile 6 - 6:18min/mi
I finally hit my target pace for this mile but it was already to late 😅 I had already spent half the race recovering from my side stitch that I just felt wiped!

Finish - 5:26min/mi
A very welcomed downhill finish and a sigh of relief. Proud that I ran through and finished with a hard effort. 
•
Thanks @cowharborrace and @elitefeats for organizing!

#roadtoparis2024 #teamsingapore #lohkeanyew #seagames31', 'A good read: https://www.straitstimes.com/sport/commentary-if-ns-rightly-comes-first-should-we-complain-if-a-swimmer-comes-second - this commentary by Rohit Brijnath in The Straits Times comes in response to Joseph’s comments at the SEA Games. 

“I think there is a lot of room to work with. As a swimmer, it’s pretty challenging to be stuck in the middle of what the nation expects you to be as an athlete representing the nation versus the things that you can commit to, like training requirements or the time needed to do the things you need to. It’s about time we had a national dialogue, we all sat down together and discussed, what are the expectations our athletes are facing. National Service is something we all need to do and no one is shying away from that. We need to manage expectations, the reality of that. At the end of the day, I'm gonna step up there and do my best no matter if I'm in the shape I am or not. But as the people watching on TV, they have a lot of expectations. We as athletes we want to match those expectations. So it's all about how we can both grow together and how sporting achievements can coincide. And I think we're on the right track - we just need to sit down, ask some tough questions. It's going to be rough, but I think we're going to come out on the right side at the end of the day." — Joseph Schooling 

I agree with what Joseph said and I think that National Service and sports can co-exist. Ultimately, we are all defending the same flag and want to do Singapore proud. 🇸🇬', 'Let’s rock and roll!! SEA Games, here we come! 😄

(Apologies for my bad running form. I tried. Not that great on land 🤣)", 'Beautiful Birmingham - It was surreal coming back to a Games Village. Spectators packed the stands, donning the red and white feels like a homecoming 2nd Comm Games. 

Back to back majors since SEA Games in May and pretty much on the road living out of my suitcase since. Deep down I was starving for a faster time than Hanoi, all the stars were aligned but often it isn’t enough. 

Frustrating as it is, I can always lean on the amazing experiences and memories forged, definitely one of my best outings in that regard. 

For now, I’m racing off the blocks to my loved ones back home and finally a short holiday to take in all the ebbs and flows of the year.

I wouldn’t be where I am today without my family, friends and all of the support staff. You guys are my pillar of strength. Thank you ❤️

I’m not taking my eyes off 2024 though 😉

This post will highlight how I love to be underwater and how the quietness and stillness underwater help me achieve my zen mode and reconnect with what I truly love about the sport.

I have a habit/routine where I like to end off each training session warming down without my goggles on just so I can truly feel the water. The stillness and quietness underwater bring me to a zen mode and recalibrates my mind, no matter how bad I feel or tired I am - the blurred vision and the sound of flowing water always brings me back to my “why”. 📸 : @wheelie_wonka', 'Beginning 2019 till date has been a whirlwind of a journey to say the least. From endless travels, competitions & training camps, to nothingness. The momentum & flow that I’ve gotten used to came to a grinding halt for the first time for as long as I could remember. 

Being an athlete in a pandemic laden world is a mixed bag of emotions. While we try to stick to our process and our normal, it was apparent that the circumstances surrounding us were changing in immeasurable ways. Almost like trying to keep constant pace against opposite currents. 

After my race on Sunday, still gasping for air from the no breathers max effort 50m swim, @quahtingwen turned to me and said, “Every 4 years, we train for this moment, and we are back where we first started again.” 

We were both immensely disappointed with our swims but somehow still mustered strength to joke about the irony of swimming in circles. Then the tsunami of emotions finally hit and I wondered into the abyss of questioning if everything was worth it. 

We chase that high, that high when we drop 0.29 seconds in a 50m. That rush. It’s us against the clock. Not anybody or anything else.

I don’t think I’ve ever trained harder in my life for something I so desperately desired. I was micro managing every aspect of my life - from recovery, training, nutrition to psychology. It came so naturally to me. 

But that is just how Sports is, - certainly even how Life is at times. We give our all, control every minutia, only to see outcome that is simply not commensurate with the effort we have put in. But we get back at it again.

I realised that the reward for my diligence cannot be viewed solely as a timing on a board. The bonds forged with my team mates, the memories of our deepest struggles and most importantly, the courage to give it my all, tell the world about it and accepting whatever the results were. To stand tall & proud of simply leaving everything on the deck. I am extremely grateful to have the privilege to do this. (But ngl, will be even more grateful with an A cut 🤣)

Don’t get to spend much time with each other so making the most of the small windows of opportunity. 🙏🇹🇭', '[Stand By Our Local Athletes Through Their Not So Glory Days]

Takagi Ramen stands by Joseph Schooling. Many of us make mistakes. Not all of us own up and face the consequences with courage. True to the bravery of an Olympic Champion, Joseph owned up to using cannabis in the past despite there not being any evidence against him - his urine tested negative for cannabis. 

How many of us are brave enough to admit to something if there is a high chance that we can get away with it?

It’s very common for people to smoke cannabis overseas, athlete or not. It’s almost as common as beer. Elite athletes have enjoyed cannabis while enjoying success in their sports careers - Michael Phelps and Diego Maradona are prime examples that you can be at the top of the world and have a little fun as well.

Smoking cannabis will not affect Jo’s career. But the outsized overreactions by our society could really affect his mental health. We hope that as Singaporeans, we can handle the situation sensibly, and support our champion as he picks himself up.

For at Takagi Ramen, we have always believed in second chances.

Reminder - Don’t smoke cannabis in Singapore! Drugs is not good for you! If you want to have fun, come to our Marine Parade outlet. We serve alcohol at supermarket prices 24/7 but please take everything in moderation, alochol can be very addictive too!

#supportlocalatheletes #secondchances #takagiramen', 'Key points:
1) Marijuana/Cannabis is not a banned drug out of competition.
2) @josephschooling never tested positive. He confessed to using marijuana in Vietnam after being implicated by association with another swimmer. The details of how exactly this investigation unfolded are not being reported clearly by the mainstream media.
3) The use of marijuana in no way provided Jo with an illegal performance enhancing advantage. I also feel this should be emphasised by the media.

On a macro level, Singapore just needs to grow up. Anyone who’s been outside this little island would know we are a laughing stock to the world because of some of these laws. Banning cannabis use in Singapore is reasonable. Banning Singaporeans from smoking cannabis overseas, is overreaching, extraterritorial, and I believe unnecessary.

📸: @vroomshoots', '“Just attack the race and smash it as hard as you can. If you die, you die brave.” - these were the final words I said aloud to myself on my warmup jog last night, after spending the last 3 weeks hobbling around with a tight hip (just look at my strava) and wondering whether I’d be recovered enough for the one race I organise in my home country every year. Thankfully, my fitness did not betray me, and I did not die: I ran a PB and under the old Singapore record (6:52) with a 6:50 finishing time.

Truth be told I was slightly annoyed at myself for not getting a sub 6min 50sec 2.4km last night. The @pocarisg 2.4km only comes around once a year so you don’t get many chances to get it right. I was in good shape in June/July but a hip strain at the end of July has made August a month of very little training. Last week, I was limping on the track, and had to cut a workout short after just 1km and almost pulled the plug on this race, but decided to wait it out. It’s a miracle I managed to run like I did last night, but it also shows that in running it’s often mind over matter.

Any disappointment at failing to go below my arbitrary goal of 6:50 however soon dissipated once seeing my supporters and loved ones after the race. They don’t really care about track, or how fast or slow I ran, and if anything are just proud and impressed by how much I attacked the race with everything I had. That provides the perspective I need to file this away as a good race given the circumstances, but more importantly, an effort I can be proud of and one I will look to emulate in the future.

Often I look back at races and wish I attacked earlier. Last night I know I took the lead early and aggressively squeezed every ounce out of my legs, but just didn’t have it on the day for my ‘A’ goal. 

Nothing much left to do then, then to get in even better shape, and smash it again next year!', 'Grabbed the lead super early and gave this race everything I had today. Was thrilled to go under the old Singapore record for 2.4km - 6:50! 
@gunnerjee stuck close and used his 1500m speed to pip me at the death - well played. Very exciting racing and these are the races I live for. 5 guys under 7 minutes today and 4 Singaporeans!
Thanks @pocarisg and @sporeathletics for another amazing event!', '#Sub7

Tonight will be the last time @gunnerjee, @ethanyan01, and myself compete together on Singapore soil for a while. Thereafter, Jeevaneesh will go to Melbourne 🇦🇺 to pursue a master’s degree in engineering, Ethan will go to Wisconsin 🇺🇸 for a degree in computer science, and I will return to London 🇬🇧 to continue my law degree.

Jeevaneesh is one of the most disciplined and “guai” athletes I know - he lives, reads, breathes and watches running. He particularly excels at the 1500m distance, having a personal best of 4:00, from this year’s SEA Games final.

Ethan is one of the most talented young 1500m runners Singapore has ever had, as well as one of the best teammates I’ve ever had, always doing his part to help when the going gets tough in training. He has a personal best of 4:04, also from this year’s SEA Games final.

We started training together at the start of 2021 under the constraints of COVID-19 lockdown, with the company of many of our fantastic training partners and Coach Steven Quek. Both these guys played a huge part of the 5,000m and marathon national records I set in 2021, and I also dragged them to their best ever 1500m performances that qualified them for the SEA Games for the first time (in 1500m).

Thank you for being amazing friends and training partners. Here’s to one last good race together at the @pocarisg 2.4km Challenge! Jeevaneesh and I will look to repeat our sub 7 min performances, while Ethan aims to break 7 minutes for the first time.

It was a very close race as a long train of runners approached the halfway point of the race. Nick Impey (@nick_impey) of Britain accidentally tripped Singapore's Ethan Yan (@ethanyan01) after running too close behind, resulting in Ethan losing his balance and falling to the ground.

Nick and the runners behind thankfully managed to hurdle over Ethan and avoid further accidents, but Ethan, a favourite to win the race, was in dead last and way off the lead by this point.

As seen in the video, Nick not only looked back to check if Ethan was ok, but came to a complete stop, turned around and encouraged Ethan to get back on his feet and into the race. Nick even voluntarily dropped into last place and encouraged Ethan from behind. Dropping back to help Ethan easily cost Nick about 5 seconds plus all his momentum.

Nick eventually overtook every runner except one to finish in second place (7min 13sec), just 1 second behind the winner, Shaun Goh. It would be fair to say that Nick sacrificed his chance at winning in the name of sportsmanship.

Ethan also displayed good fighting spirit to finish the race, running fast enough (7:17) to qualify for the elite race on August 20 - It promises to be a good race with record holder Jeevaneesh (@gunnerjee) and myself. He has also graciously praised Nick for his act of sportsmanship on Instagram.

In a day and age where winning is often prioritised over values, Nick's sportsmanship deserves to be celebrated and recognised, as does Ethan's fighting spirit. Do help share this video and help make the world a better place through sports!

['When dreams die, a part of our hearts too. 😪 I broke down uncontrollably when I heard 2 cracks from my ankle when I slipped and fell while running yesterday. I bore a sliver of hope that it's a bad sprain. When I first heard the word "fracture" at the hospital, I bawled uncontrollably. Diagnosis - a displaced fracture of the fibula and operation ensued to maximise chances of smooth recovery. 7 screws inserted and today 14 April marks my first day of recovery. It'll be a long hard road filled with tears and frustration but I can only keep moving forward. Yesterday I was running, today I can barely walk but one day I'll be running again.

#lovelivelaughrun #nevergiveup #downbutnotout #keepitreal #motherrunner #theCheesiblings', "Every November, I reminisce about the most memorable and incredible marathon I've ever ran - the Antarctic Ice Marathon. A bunch of crazy/enthusiastic runners travelled to Antarctica keen to challenge ourselves and realise our dreams. 
#
Running 42.195km in -20s°C cold/snowy conditions seemed almost impossible but the camaraderie among runners and more importantly, the desire to realise my dream of running a marathon on all 7 continents in memory of my late grandmother and to raise funds for the elderly pushed me along every step of the way. I've never felt more humbled, grateful and emotional crossing the finish line of a marathon as this one. 
#

#lovelivelaughrun #NewBalanceSG #KeepingItReal #theCHEEsiblings #sgrunners", "Not too long ago, I used to say that “sleep’s a waste of time” and prided myself on getting by with 4-5h sleep daily. My post-partum 2018 return to marathon running was essentially fuelled by 3-5h sleep daily coz of breastfeeding and a crying baby - can’t imagine how I did that 😵‍💫? 

These days, I’m a convert and finally understand what everyone means when they say that sleep’s the best form of recovery. I’m making a conscious effort to go to bed earlier and waking up to my Polar Grit X Pro telling me that I’ve had a “very good” night recharge gives me a good idea of how hard I can push for my training - all about listening to the body!

Info - the Polar Nightly Recharge is Polar's version of sleep tracking which shows how well one has slept and recovered during the night.

Sleep Charge is relatively straightforward, measuring the amount and quality of sleep each night. It’s a classic sleep metric, looking at the hours of rest and sleep cycles, then comparing them to the previous 28 days to see how well one has rested. 

Autonomic Nervous System Charge measures how well the autonomic nervous system calmed down during the first hours of sleep compared to the usual level over the previous 28 days.

The combination of these two scores makes Polar’s Nightly Recharge very comprehensive. Think of them as a sleep quantity and a sleep quality measurement.

#lovelivelaughrun #listentothebody #NewBalanceSG #PolarSingapore #Nuzest #TeamRDRC #SundayShadesCo #theCHEEsiblings #motherrunner', 'The Last Time

From the moment you hold your baby in your arms,
you will never be the same.
You might long for the person you were before,
When you have freedom and time,
And nothing in particular to worry about.

You will know tiredness like you never knew it before,
And days will run into days that are exactly the same,
Full of feedings and burping,
Nappy changes and crying,
Whining and fighting,
Naps or a lack of naps,
It might seem like a never-ending cycle.

But don’t forget …
There is a last time for everything.
There will come a time when you will feed your baby for the very last time.
They will fall asleep on you after a long day
And it will be the last time you ever hold your sleeping child.

One day you will carry them on your hip then set them down,
And never pick them up that way again.
You will scrub their hair in the bath one night
And from that day on they will want to bathe alone.
They will hold your hand to cross the road,
Then never reach for it again.
They will creep into your room at midnight for cuddles,
And it will be the last night you ever wake to this.

One afternoon you will sing “the wheels on the bus” and do all the actions,
Then never sing them that song again.
They will kiss you goodbye at the school gate,
The next day they will ask to walk to the gate alone.
You will read a final bedtime story and wipe your last dirty face.
They will run to you with arms raised for the very last time.

The thing is, you won’t even know it’s the last time
Until there are no more times.
And even then, it will take you a while to realize.

So while you are living in these times,
remember there are only so many of them
and when they are gone, you will yearn for just one more day of them.
For one last time.

–Joanthan Fanning–

Living, loving and cherishing these times of “Mama, we haven’t taken our wefie today” before the ‘last time’ unexpectedly creeps up on me 🥲.

Seriously though, I’ve surprised myself in this journey. I’ve always been wary / scared / somewhat against strength training coz I thought:

1. I don’t have time for it. Might as well run with that 1 hour.
2. It’s stressful having someone watch over me.
3. I don’t know what to do. What if I injure myself?

This thinking started to change when @coyotefitness so generously guided me with a strength programme after my ankle fracture last year. Then I started a structured programme around 2 months ago and am making small gains.

Why do I do it? It was a missing piece of the puzzle - can’t keep doing the same thing and expecting different results. Plus strength training helps to retain muscle mass as I age, prevent injury (muscles more equipped to handle load), and I get to vary my training. Still a noob in the gym but under the guidance of Danny and Joshua, I’m slowly making improvements - actually squatting above my body weight now 😉. #CelebrateEveryWin

#lovelivelaughrun #strengthtraining #NewBalanceSG #PolarSingapore #TeamRDRC #Nuzest #theCHEEsiblings', 'Something I say a lot/believe in these days - it’s not really about how much you train but how well you recover and reap the gains from the training + stay injury-free especially as we age. That’s why I’m always open to trying different recovery methods and one that I’ve stuck with over the years is red light therapy. 

LightStim MultiWave® treatment at @hellophysiosg ➡️ a LED light bed that accelerates the body's recovery process in 20-minute sessions a couple of times each week.

Oxidative stress is the underlying issue for most degenerative dysfunctions and diseases. By stimulating adenosine triphosphate (ATP) synthesis, the FDA-cleared red and infrared light normalizes and improves mitochondrial function.

Also known as "photobiomodulation”, LightStim improves blood circulation, increases the rate of recovery after injuries, decreases pain and inflammation, boosts energy levels, improves muscle performance, aids in sleep, and has a host of other benefits. This, in turn, activates the body's healing response in treating acute or chronic musculoskeletal injuries from
tendinopathies to osteoarthritis.

While the technical jargon may sound kinda out of this world and 20min may seem like a short time but that’s the beauty of it and it’s working from inside out, at the cellular level. Bio-hacking!

#inspire', "Dare to BeWhen a new day begins, dare to smile gratefully. When there is darkness, dare to be the first to shine a light. When there is injustice, dare to be the first to condemn it. When something seems difficult, dare to do it anyway. When life seems to beat you down, dare to fight back. When there seems to be no hope, dare to find some. When you're feeling tired, dare to keep going. When times are tough, dare to be tougher. When love hurts you, dare to love again. When someone is hurting, dare to help them heal. When another is lost, dare to help them find the way. When a friend falls, dare to be the first to extend a hand. When you cross paths with another, dare to make them smile. When you feel great, dare to help someone else feel great too. When the day has ended, dare to feel as you've done your best. Dare to be the best you can. At all times, Dare to be!
~Steve Maraboli

✨𝐇𝐚𝐦𝐛𝐞𝐥𝐚 𝐓𝐫𝐞𝐚𝐬𝐮𝐫𝐞 ($7)
< orange blossom, lychee & melon, peach tea >', '📍Apartment

commemorating my first visit to their new home hence another post! setting was really similar to their old space with the addition of more seats. clean neutrals with a touch of plant life. 

✨𝐂𝐨𝐬𝐭𝐚 𝐑𝐢𝐜𝐚 𝐀𝐪𝐮𝐢𝐚𝐫𝐞𝐬 𝐄𝐬𝐭𝐚𝐭𝐞 ($7)
< red apple, grapefruit, chocolate >

getting the juice again!!! clearly fell into the deep hole of hand brews… i end up getting hand brews every time i’m here instead of my usual. on my first sip, i could taste the red apple and grapefruit, not so much the chocolate. its so interesting how they all look similar but yet taste so different. 

✨𝐎𝐚𝐭 𝐖𝐡𝐢𝐭𝐞 (𝐁𝐫𝐚𝐳𝐢𝐥 𝐅𝐚𝐫𝐫𝐨𝐮𝐩𝐢𝐥𝐡𝐚)($5.50)
< sweet chocolate, pecan, baked apples >', '📍Micro Bakery

it’s been a while since i’ve been this excited about toast. i’ve been wanting to come here for the longest time for their seasonal ricotta toast!! i’ve tried their tomato ricotta tartine previously but the one i really really wanted to try was their seasonal version!!! i’ve missed out on the apple and persimmon renditions which im still so sad about. BUT i’ve been keeping my eyes peeled for new versions of their seasonal ricotta toast! saw that they are having a rock melon one now and got so excited!!! it’s one of my favourite fruits 😋

their ricotta toast always seem to use such interesting toppings which are uncommonly used (apple jelly? sour plum powder? jackfruit? rhubarb?)! where else would you see all these!! can’t wait to see what other innovative combinations the team comes up with 😍😍😍!!! 

✨𝐑𝐢𝐜𝐨𝐭𝐭𝐚 𝐓𝐨𝐚𝐬𝐭 𝐰𝐢𝐭𝐡 𝐑𝐨𝐜𝐤 𝐌𝐞𝐥𝐨𝐧 ($11)
toast was fluffy with a slight chew! could taste the sour tang thats so iconic of sourdough!! the mint leaves adds a refreshing taste at the end of each bite. the sweetness from the rock melon jam with the creaminess from the ricotta and the sweet-sour taste from the sour plum powder sprinkled on top was really an experience!!! theres so many things going on on the plate but yet they all balance out so well with so many textures as well😍🤩😋😋!!! so beautiful 💯💯!!

✨𝐈𝐜𝐞𝐝 𝐖𝐡𝐢𝐭𝐞 ($6)', '📍Bloom Coffee

got here after taking a 40 mins walk with @nibsandgobs ahhahaa. really lovely vibes! a little out of the way but perfect for a solo date, to read or pitstop after a run! (you get to dog watch 🐶 if you’re lucky hahahaha) 

✨𝐈𝐜𝐞𝐝 𝐁𝐥𝐚𝐜𝐤 ($5)
*double shots 

✨𝐖𝐡𝐢𝐭𝐞 (5oz) ($5)
*single shot

✨𝐅𝐫𝐢𝐞𝐝 𝐂𝐚𝐮𝐥𝐢𝐟𝐥𝐨𝐰𝐞𝐫 ($11)

rarely do i ever drink blacks but this was quite a drink 😋😋 nothing too sour or over the top, quite ‘refreshing’! the white was quite nice and comforting! not too milky and pretty smooth drink

didn’t get their tater tots that day because we wanted to try something different. got the fried cauliflower instead. not sure if it was just a batch issue or if its actual intentions were meant to be so but the interior was a little near-mushy, could afford to be a little crisper in texture! nothing amazing tho! sauce could be more flavourful too 😢😢

overall i’ll head back for their coffee and try their sangas and toast while i’m at it 💖', '📍Supernova 

✨𝐅𝐫𝐢𝐞𝐝 𝐂𝐡𝐢𝐜𝐤𝐞𝐧 𝐅𝐫𝐞𝐧𝐜𝐡 𝐓𝐨𝐚𝐬𝐭 ($24.50)
my 2nd ever fried chicken toast/waffles in my life and lets just say this was SO GUD!!!! im a huge sweet-salty combo person so this was right up my alley 🤩🤩 the chicken was well seasoned, juicy and crispy. shokupan itself was soft, fluffy and gorgeously toasted. the garlic compound butter and spiced maple syrup was the perfect cherry on top!! shared this with a friend and didn’t feel that it was surfeiting! definitely lived up to the highly raved reviews 😋

✨𝐁𝐚𝐜𝐨𝐧 & 𝐏𝐮𝐦𝐩𝐤𝐢𝐧 𝐑𝐢𝐠𝐚𝐭𝐨𝐧𝐢 ($21)
this was another one that i’ve seen quite a few people having! i was quite drawn to it because pumpkin isn’t an ingredient thats commonly used in pasta dishes here! sadly, i don’t remember this plate being anything special. despite being cream based, it doesnt taste very jelat. couldn’t really taste the pumpkin in the sauce tho! pretty generous with the bacon bits and mushrooms, enough for every bite. there was also a puzzling thick piece of baguette on the plate 😂(if it’s suppose to be eaten w the sauce, i’m afraid theres not enough sauce for that).

✨𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐌𝐢𝐥𝐤𝐲 𝐖𝐚𝐲 ($7.70)
this cold brew has been recommended to me multiple times but i must say i’m abit disappointed by it 😪 i’ll skip this during my next visit to any of their outlets!', '📍Apartment

✨𝐊𝐢𝐰𝐚𝐦𝐢 𝐖𝐚𝐠𝐲𝐮 𝐒𝐮𝐤𝐢𝐲𝐚𝐤𝐢 𝐃𝐨𝐧 ($29.90)

the minute i sank my teeth into the rice, my eyebrows knotted and my entire face sang Mmmm mmm mmmmm 😍😍😍 the entire meal. me being the 饭桶 (rice bucket) i am, i loved the rice drizzled with the sauce so much 😍😍

as you dig further into the bowl, you’ll discover an entire block of tofu, vermicelli, mushrooms and cabbage. honestly the bowl doesnt look very big but by the end of the meal, my stomach was STUFFED!!! honestly a 💯 would return anytime im craving a good don 🤤🤤. you don’t even have to splurge on the wagyu because they have a $14.90 beef don option too!! super worth imo!! 

only downside is the limited dining space which inevitably leads to a long waiting time but i guess thats the concept of the store. be prepared to queue. i’ll recommend going early and in small groups (2-3pax) due to the sitting style!! matcha bun [$2.80❗️i just found out price increased to $3😟]:
GUYS. GO GET THIS IT’S SO GOOD. am so glad i chanced upon this in takashimaya. i saw some reviews about this and knew it was in taka but didn’t know exactly where the bread shop was until i was casually walking around and it caught my eyes (my face literally went through 4 stages 😮🤭😄🤩) the soft and chewy green tea bun is covered with a generous amount of matcha crumble and green tea powder. the bitterness from the unsweetened green tea powder and slightly sweet crumble cookie added a crunchy texture to the bun. and look at that oozy matcha lava!!! the matcha filling was intense and earthy, legit super amazing👍🏻👍🏻 thought the reddish dark brown cream at the bottom is red bean but it’s actually chocolate which adds a slight sweetness to the bitter matcha taste.

toasting this matcha bun results in a crispy exterior for that crunch on the outside yet the interior of the bun is still soft and fluffy, and for that oozy matcha lava texture!! yay a post for one of my favourite neighbourhood bakery which is literally 5 minutes away from my house!!! woohoo🤟🏻🤟🏻 i also like how they rotate their bakes for surprises 🥳 so far i’ve tried most of their different donut flavours, eclairs, friands, cheesecake, lemon meringue bars and they never fail to amaze me!!!! last week i got the sour cream and chives donut, mascarpone cheesecake and dark choco babka😋😋 but this post will solely be reviewing the donut and the next post for the cheesecake and babka!

sour cream and chives donut [$3.80]:
ooooo this is interesting because sour cream and chives filling in a donut puff?? 😯😯 i personally like this filling, it’s so pleasant to the palate. it has this light creaminess yet slight tangy-ness. if you don’t feel like eating donuts with sweet fillings, u can try this savoury filling donut!! the chives adds that savoury umami? (i think that’s what you call it opss) flavour. there’s chopped up chives in the filling as well!! this sour cream & chives donut doesn’t have sugar coated around like their other donut flavours, instead there’s black and white sesame seeds on the donut for that extra texture. 
and as always, their puffs never disappoint. its fluffy and soft yet crispy on the outside, and it’s not super oily. hmMmmM so amazinggg. another good thing is they are super!! generous!!! with!! the!! fillings!!!! i think for this donut flavour, it can be eaten cold/hot but i didn’t refrigerated it nor heat up and it’s still good👍🏻 so addictive for me because i was suppose to eat half and give the other half to my bro but i couldn’t resist it and finish the whole donut✌🏻✌🏻it’s alright guys he can still buy it this weekend 😬 anyway, y’all should give this a try!!

almond croissant [$4]:

KL's hidden rooftop coffee bar, which was inspired by a love of camping, has set up camping tent on The Row's second floor in Chow Kit⛺️ It is hard to find a pet friendly cafe yet serving great and quality food 🐩

Tuna Tsu Yu (RM27)
japan style stir fried pasta with tuna, mushroom, served with mentaiko and seaweed🐟the pasta was moist and not hard or dry. tuna and mentaiko are made for each other\U0001f979

Lychee Rose Ice Tea (RM18)🍹

🍉Summer Watermelon Cake (RM18)
it’s absolutely fantastic, there’s a slice of refreshing watermelon with a hint of light rose-scented cream, topped off with strawberries and edible rose petals🍓it’s super refreshing, not too sweet and as the texture of a cake. when I first saw it I highly doubted it since the combination of watermelon in a cake sounded soggy and odd to me🤷🏻‍♀️to my surprise it was not soggy at all and gave it a very unique texture\U0001f979

We went there for an afternoon tea on weekday (no crowd, and didn’t get meet up cute furry friends there \U0001f972🐾) and we found out this is really a perfect place when hanging out or when relaxing away from home. Will definitely be back again, for sure 😼

the mochi is not the chewy kind but liquid-y and melt in your mouth. the amount of mochi is INSANELY GENEROUS, they literally stuffed every empty nook and cranny of the interior with mochi (not gonna lie, the puff is HEFTY and most of the weight comes from the mochi🙈) so expect each bite to be an explosion of sticky and sweet mochi. 🍡

however, the chocolate/peanut flavours are quite overpowered by the sheer amount of mochi and i wish there were more of those fillings to make the whole pastry more flavourful! 

still, i enjoyed these mochi puffs overall and they 𝗱𝗲𝗳𝗶𝗻𝗶𝘁𝗲𝗹𝘆 satisfied my mochi cravings 🙈 i love the idea of incorporating the mochi trend into traditional old school puffs and i would recommend everyone to have a try 👍🏼 let’s support our local bakeries and their innovations! ☺️

🍛Hakka Tofu Bowl ($5.50)

So I’ve seen mixed reviews about this tofu bowl but I really thought it was good. It was fusion done right to me and I’ve since had many more bowls on separate occasions while enjoying them all the same.

I was a little apprehensive of the mayonnaise at first, because how well could it go with something that is in reminiscence of 擂茶饭? But then I had a go at it and I thought it was something that the bowl couldn’t do without. 😳

The fried chicken pieces were kinda like the highlight of the meal. They remind me of karaage, but stuffed in crispy fried tofu puff that were made even better with their mayonnaise and sweet chilli dip. 🤤', '🦦✨
📍Sushiro, Causeway Point

Sometimes I do crave for a convenient, fuss free sushi dinner and Sushiro seems to tick all the boxes for me. 👌
 
🍳Energy Boost Inari ($2.20)
🥩A5 Miyazaki Galbi Beef ($4.80)
🐟Salmon with Basil Cheese ($2.20)
🥩A5 Miyazak Roast Beef ($4.80)
🐟Premium Salmon Belly ($3.20)
🐟Marinated Broiled Salmon ($2.20)

My favourite of the lot was definitely the Energy Boost Inari. Slivers of beef and onion with a quarter of seasoned egg were all flavourful. The sushi was definitely on the sweeter side because of the tofu pocket but I enjoyed it regardless.

Both the A5 Miyazaki Beef sushi weren’t shabby too, they were pretty tender. I liked the accompanying sauce on the roast beef although they were nothing to shout about.

The Salmon with Basil Cheese had so much potential. I thought the herbaceous notes of the basil sauce was yummy but it was too heavy with the torched salmon and cheese. A touch more basil would do the trick though.', '🦦✨
