\U0001f9cbChrysanthemum Tea with Chrysanthemum Pearls at 0% Sugar Level

This might be a case of chrysanthemum overdose but their chrysanthemum pearls are so good. They are fragrant and their pearls have a good kind of chew that’s unique to Playmade. 🌼

Even at 0% sugar level, my drink was lightly sweetened and perfect for me.. Although I must say I’m the kind of hate unsweetened teas from bubble tea shops. 🌚', '🦦✨
📍Techno Edge Canteen, NUS Faculty of Engineering
🍛Ayam Hijau Nasi Lemak

I got this nasi lemak because I thought the butterfly pea rice looked really pretty! Alas, it was covered by that huge slab of chicken thigh and omelette when it arrived. 😂

Not complaining because I enjoyed both proteins as far as regular lunches go.. And the green chilli sambal was lovely with the chicken heh. 👌', '🦦✨
📍Marche Movenpick, 313 Somerset
🍕Smoked Duck Hoisin Pizza ($22.90)

Think Peking Duck but in a crispy, thin crust pizza form! With tomatoes and cheese! Although they could be a little more generous with the smoked duck, I enjoyed this sweet and savoury combination a lot. And I’ll definitely order this again the next time I visit. 🤓', '🦦✨
📍MacPherson Minced Meat Noodles
🍜Minced Meat Noodles ($4.50)

This was no doubt a good bowl of 肉脞面 that I enjoyed. The vinegared sauce mix was fragrant, punchy and had a good kick, although I got myself another tablespoon of vinegar for good luck. But that’s just me, I’ve always been the ✨多✨醋少辣 kind of person.

The minced meat, pork slices and pork liver slivers tasted really fresh too but what I love the most was that bowl of soup. It looked unassuming but it was anything so. It was flavourful yet light and paired well with the saucy bowl of noodles.

I’ll definitely go for the 小碗面 next time! More soup and more ingredients means more goodness. And it seems like they serve 面线 too so I’m looking forward. 🤗', '🦦✨
📍So Good Char Chan Tang, Midview City

Not my first visit to So Good but there are still so many dishes that I want to try, like their Curry Beef Brisket Rice! But probably not at Midview City, at least a couple of their staff were incredibly rude. 🙄\U0001f972

🍅Baked Tomato Pork Chop Rice ($9.50)
🍖Twin Combination Meat Rice with Roast Duck and Roast Pork ($7.50)
🍲Macaroni with Luncheon Meat and Fried Egg ($4.50)
🍳Scrambled Egg Thick Toast ($3.50)
🧈Polo Bun with Butter ($2.30)
☕️Hong Kong Style Milk Tea ($2.20)

My favourite of the lot would definitely be the Baked Tomato Pork Chop Rice! I’m wondering if the baking actually made any difference to the dish, but I loved the tangy and slightly sweet tomato sauce! The pork chop itself was also tender and served generously. 🤤

The Polo Bun with Butter was good too! Really fluffy bun, with a good amount of crispy sweet crust and chilled butter; this could be my favourite polo bun in Singapore. 🤝

The Scrambled Egg Thick Toast on the other hand was just alright. I had it once with my bread untoasted and I much preferred that heh. The egg here was really silky and not a smidge overcooked but it could really do well with a little salt and pepper.. I’m pretty sure it was unseasoned. 🤪', '🦦✨
📍Old Hen Coffee

Happy International Coffee Day everyone! Just leaving a photo of my favourite cold brews ever, when they were still in their OG bottles.

☕️Cold Mocha ($7.50)
🍫Valrhona Dark Cocoa ($6.50)

Both of them, along with their white cold brew, were so good! They were thick, velvety smooth with just the right amount of sweetness. Technicalities aside since I’m far from being a coffee connoisseur, I just love how they tasted. 💯🤤', '🦦✨
📍Merci Marcel Orchard, Palais Renaissance

One of my favourite places to be at; I love their vibes, their energy and their food.

🥟Ravioles de Royans ($18)
🐟Beetroot Carpaccio & Wild Trout Gravlax ($11)
🥐Croissant ($3.50)
☕️Mocha ($6)

The ravioli and cured trout might seem like an unlikely pairing but they went so well together! The vodka and honey marinade of the trout was a sweet and a little acidic and it complimented the richness of the pasta so well. 🥺

The croissant was not the very best but I enjoyed it enough! It wasn’t stale and was pretty light. I had my fair share of worse ones at higher price points so I would definitely order this again. 🤟', '🦦✨
📍Greendot, Northpoint City

I usually avoid cai pngs like the plague and I can never seem to vibe with vegetables. But I make exceptions for Greendot and it is one of the only few places that makes me crave for plants and fungi. 👀🌚

🍱Bento with 2 Mains and 1 Green ($10.90)
🍚Brown Rice
🍄Gong Bao Mixed Mushroom (+$1)
🧆Sweet and Sour Soya Nuggets
🥘Vegetable Curry

I was so contented with my choices because all of them were so yummy and up my alley! Very flavourful but I don’t find them too oily like how some regular cai pngs can get. Maybe because they don’t drench the sauce all over my rice?

But ah, I felt a bit sian at the soup because even Greendot can’t make me appreciate dried seaweed. I would much prefer their regular winter melon soup but it just wasn’t my day. 😔', '🦦✨
📍Tamago EN, Causeway Point
🍛Beef Stew Omu Rice ($16.90)

So it is all about their eggs here and I thought mine was pretty decent! It was silky and tasted fresh, although nothing too mind blowing. The beef chunks were tender enough and the demi-glace was flavourful, just a tad too salty for me. I did change my butter rice to plain ones and I thought they went better that way heh. 🤝', '🦦✨
📍Don Don Donki, Jem

They might not serve the best Japanese food around but it’s usually very value for money! Their servings are huge and I always feel so contended shopping for some noms there. 😌

🍱Mega Bento Salmon and Chicken Karaage ($11.80)
🍗Black Vinegar Chicken Karaage ($5.90)
🧁Custard Waffle Cakes ($4.90)

I honestly thought the bento was just alright. I’d prefer if chicken and salmon were more tender. Same thing with the Black Vinegar Chicken Karaage, it was a little tough but it’s still a repeat purchase as I really enjoyed the sauce! 👍

But the best thing on that table was definitely the waffle cakes. I got it because I couldn’t find the elusive Souffle Roll but this was so much better for me. Imagine soft and fluffy sponge with sweet cream filling and luckily, they weren’t too milky. I liked it so much that I could finish four at a go. And I did. 🤤🌚', '🦦✨
📍Heytea, Westgate
\U0001f9cbSoymilk Bobo ($7.80)

I thought this cup of milk tea would get a little confusing because there’s just so many things going on at the same time? There’s soymilk cream, soymilk pudding, soybean powder and even taro bobo. But then I took the plunge and got it anyway. And I loved it. 🤭

The soymilk cream on top was my favourite of them all. It was rich and creamy but not sickly so. And the earthy and roasty notes from the soy bean powder was moreish and simply delightful. 🥺', '🦦✨
📍7-Eleven
☕️HY Hot Brew Macadamia Mocha Latte

As far as bottled coffees go, this was really not that bad after all. Although a little too sweet for my liking, I’ll still drink this willingly to collect even more pretty bottles. 🌚

P.S. Also happy five years to the greatest alter ego there ever is. 😘🤤✌️', '🦦✨
📍Common Man Coffee Roasters, Fort Canning MRT Station
🍞Brioche French Toast ($22)

Not the eggiest French toast around, but definitely the softest and fluffiest that I’ve tried! Also loved that sprinkle of ground cinnamon that added some warmth to my toast. 😌', '🦦✨
📍Homemade 🤲
🍜Beef Noodles Soup

Always feeling lucky to have friends who cook really well and even more fortunate to be fed by them! And this precious bowl of beef noodle soup was just too good. Even the lovely noodles were handmade by my friend himself. 🤓', '🦦✨
📍Denzy, Bishan MRT Station

This has been on my list to visit for so long but I held it off because I’m just not one to crave for frozen desserts. But damn, these gelatos were enjoyable.

🧇Light and Crispy Waffle with Gelato ($14.10)
🍨Roasted Bronte Pistachio Gelato
🍨Whisky and Salted Pecan Brittle Gelato

Came here for the pistachio gelato and I was pretty impressed! It was velvety and the roasted, earthy taste of pistachio came forth. 👍🤩

It was good but just a tad too sweet and heavy for me. That’s why I actually prefer the whisky gelato! It was less sugary and I loved munching on that generous, yummy brittle for a greater depth of flavour. 🤤

However, the waffle was a let down for me. It was a light and crispy waffle indeed but I’m not fond of the batter. It was a little savoury and tasted a little burnt for me.', '🦦✨
📍MukJja, Novena Regency
🍜Set A ($40)

Best kind of set meal to order in a Korean Chinese restaurant when you only had a friend with you but y’all just want to try everything! Or maybe it was just me. 🎉🤓

The tangsuyuk was my favourite! I loved how that whiff of the punchy vinegar attacked my nose and the pork were pretty crispy when it was served too. 🤟

Both the noodles were very onion forward and I preferred the jjajangmyeon. It was a little more sweet than it was savoury but none too overbearing. Jjamppong on the other hand, was too spicy for me and I couldn’t really taste the depth of the seafood flavour. 😬', '🦦✨
📍FlagWhite, Beauty World MRT Station

Having good food after a long hike was exceptionally rewarding indeed! I’m up for more sessions if that means I can be fed happily. 👩‍🌾

🍗Chicken Parmigiana ($15)
☕️Hot Mocha ($6)

The fried chicken was tender and juicy! The tangy tomato concasse and cheese made me felt like I was having a pizza. But better. Why choose when I can have the best of both worlds? 😎 

Although hot mochas might not be the best idea after a 10km hike, the one I had here became my favourite! It left a slight fruity and alcoholic aftertaste and now I am missing it again.

P.S. My tiny regret was forgetting to change the fries for their sweet potato ones but that was all on me. 😟', '🦦✨
📍Fu Lin Fried Yong Tau Fu, IMM
🍲Six Pieces Fried with Thick Bee Hoon and Gravy ($7.50)

Discovered this gem on @auntiekongfoodie’s feed from a while ago and thought that I should try! And definitely no regrets here. 🤟

This is my kind of yong tau fu because it was anything but healthy. The items were deep fried to a crisp and drenched with a minced meat and mushroom gravy which thankfully, wasn’t too heavily seasoned despite how it looked. 😌', '🦦✨
📍Meng’s Teochew Beef Kuay Teow, Yishun MRT Station
🥩Mixed Beef with Tendon ($5)

Not a fan of the usual dark and starchy gravy for my dry beef noodles so I thought I’d give this a try. The crazy mix of soy based sauce, sesame oil and fried shallots with perfectly blanched bean sprouts became my kind of jam indeed. 👌

Been missing this a little but on my second visit, I found out that it was gone and replaced by a 猪肠粉 stall so fml. 🌚']

['There seem to be an influx of fancy and elevated Nasi Lemak these days. The new kid on the block @wildcoco.sg prides itself on using fresh coconut milk, chicken and not using MSG.

I tried their 𝐀𝐲𝐚𝐦 𝐁𝐞𝐫𝐞𝐦𝐩𝐚𝐡 𝐋𝐞𝐠 and it indeed felt elevated. The star is the chicken, so damn tender and juicy, yet crispy-crusty on the outside. The marinate itself is a blend of spice which include lemongrass, chilli etc. Very delicious!

The other components are done really well too. I usually find nasi lemak sambal too sweet, but this had a good balance with savoury and spiciness.

I felt the flavour of the rice can be improved though - its not as Lemak as how i like it to be. The chef mentioned that they are still trying to find flavour consistency from the supply of fresh coconut.

I also had to wait 1 hour, but as i said before, i wouldnt mind waiting for good food!

Overall🥚: 8/10 🍳🍳🍳🍳🍳🍳🍳🍳

@koal.grill is a casual grill restaurant by Les Amis Group, so you know the quality going to be there.

We tried the famous 𝐊𝐎𝐀𝐋’𝐬 𝐁𝐫𝐞𝐚𝐝 𝐑𝐨𝐥𝐥, which had bits of bacon, grilled spring onion and sour cream. The bread itself is very fragrant, buttery and fluffy, savoury and good to eat on its own. Having it served on a hot pan made it extra comforting.

𝐂𝐚𝐮𝐥𝐢𝐟𝐥𝐨𝐰𝐞𝐫 𝐒𝐨𝐮𝐩 had intense flavour, with the roasted cauliflower providing a nice char and texture contrast. 

𝐑𝐨𝐚𝐬𝐭𝐞𝐝 𝐁𝐨𝐧𝐞 𝐌𝐚𝐫𝐫𝐨𝐰 was served with beef tartare, which was divine on its own. Paired with bone marrow made it a flavour bomb, so umami! 

𝐈𝐛𝐞𝐫𝐢𝐜𝐨 𝐏𝐨𝐫𝐤 𝐂𝐨𝐥𝐥𝐚𝐫 and 𝐇𝐚𝐧𝐠𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐓𝐞𝐧𝐝𝐞𝐫 were both nicely grilled with nice char. Flavour was good and had nice bite. Honestly no complains at this price point. I would recommend pairing with Sesame Chimichurri, which we couldnt stop having!

𝐇𝐨𝐣𝐢𝐜𝐡𝐚 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐖𝐡𝐢𝐬𝐤𝐲 𝐓𝐢𝐫𝐚𝐦𝐢𝐬𝐮 was a tad disappointing given how outstanding the savouries were.

All in all, @koal.grill serves quality food at reasonably affordable price. This got to be one of the most enjoyable meals I had this year.

P.S. damage was ~$140 for above + 2 alcohol

Overall🥚: 10/10 🍳🍳🍳🍳🍳🍳🍳🍳🍳🍳

@afamosa_sataycelup took over the spot where old world fried porridge used to be at. According to the shop owner, they are part of the same brand, and satay celup had been a food they been wanting to promote in Singapore. I knew i'd love it when they said the satay sauce was their grandma's recipe!

The satay sauce was like what I had in the old streets of malacca. Thick, with a good balance of sweet and savoury. 

There is a wide variety of skewer to choose from and affordably priced. Really delicious to cook it in the luscious pot of peanut. I would recommend to go for the meat skewers! 

If you been to malacca, you would have heard of the famous cheese beehoon. @afamosa_sataycelup serves a good version of it as well! 

Cockles were also really fresh - plump in texture and clean tasting. Great to go alone, or dipped into their chilli sauce or dunked into the bowl of satay. All equally enjoyable!

I didn't intend to do any posting initially but after a first few mouth, I knew i had to share this hidden find!

Overall🥚: 8.5/10 🍳🍳🍳🍳🍳🍳🍳🍳🟡

The barrier towards wide scale adoption of plant-based food had always been the inability to replace the satisfaction gained from a meat-based meal. The homely food at @lilac.oak would change your mind!

𝐌𝐢𝐬𝐨 𝐁𝐮𝐭𝐭𝐞𝐫 𝐆𝐫𝐢𝐥𝐥𝐞𝐝 𝐂𝐨𝐫𝐧 & 𝐁𝐫𝐨𝐜𝐜𝐨𝐥𝐢 was a case of extracting maximum flavour from simple ingredients. Smoky and buttery, this was our favourite dish (we paid for this!).

The winner in the 𝐏𝐞𝐚𝐧𝐮𝐭 𝐓𝐞𝐦𝐩𝐞𝐡 𝐒𝐚𝐧𝐝𝐰𝐢𝐜𝐡 is the sauce. While it's supposed to be peanut sauce, there's some special zest to it, really binding the all components together beautifully. It was surprisingly not dry at all!

𝐓𝐚𝐫𝐨 𝐓𝐚𝐫𝐭 felt almost too like the real Orh Nee. I would have preferred if it was a tad bit sweeter.

Still quite amazed at how the 𝐒𝐰𝐞𝐞𝐭 𝐏𝐨𝐭𝐚𝐭𝐨 𝐆𝐞𝐥𝐚𝐭𝐨 contained no cow milk (replaced with a mix of oat and soy). The texture is creamy and certainly better than alot of the gelatos out there. Perfect with the crispy 𝐖𝐚𝐟𝐟𝐥𝐞𝐬!

𝐈𝐜𝐞𝐝 𝐒𝐡𝐚𝐤𝐞𝐧 𝐌𝐢𝐱𝐞𝐝 𝐁𝐞𝐫𝐫𝐲 𝐄𝐚𝐫𝐥 𝐆𝐫𝐞𝐲 𝐰𝐢𝐭𝐡 𝐒𝐭𝐫𝐚𝐰𝐛𝐞𝐫𝐫𝐲 𝐏𝐞𝐚𝐫𝐥𝐬 is a refreshing drink that would complement your meal.

Overall🥚: 8/10 🍳🍳🍳🍳🍳🍳🍳🍳

The pizza at @lapizzaiolasg was so memorable I had to visit a second time!

Nested deep within a private housing estate, the pizzeria had a rustic charm to it.

Their pizza mostly have a tomato and mozzarella base. The crust was the star for me, crusty on the outside, doughy chewy on the inside. It is not overly thick and really good for eating on its own.

We had the 𝐆𝐚𝐦𝐛𝐞𝐫𝐢 𝐞 𝐂𝐚𝐥𝐚𝐦𝐚𝐫𝐢 which is their seafood option, with a drizzle of pesto sauce giving some zest.

𝐃𝐢𝐚𝐯𝐨𝐥𝐚 is no nonsense, just served with spicy beef & pork salami. Simple yet delicious!

𝐏𝐫𝐨𝐬𝐜𝐢𝐮𝐭𝐭𝐨 𝐞 𝐅𝐮𝐧𝐠𝐡𝐢 is topped with cooked ham & button mushroom. A nice contrast of savouriness at play.

We also tried the 𝐓𝐚𝐠𝐥𝐢𝐨𝐥𝐢𝐧𝐢 𝐚𝐥 𝐍𝐞𝐫𝐨 𝐝𝐢 𝐒𝐞𝐩𝐩𝐢𝐚 𝐜𝐨𝐧 𝐒𝐚𝐥𝐬𝐚 𝐝𝐢 𝐆𝐫𝐚𝐧𝐜𝐡𝐢𝐨, which is squid-ink tagliolini with crabmeat & tomato in white wine sauce. It was rather bland. I would suggest to skip pasta and go for the pizzas!

We also tried the 𝐊𝐨𝐫𝐞𝐚𝐧-𝐬𝐭𝐲𝐥𝐞 𝐁𝐞𝐞𝐟 𝐑𝐚𝐰 (𝐘𝐮𝐤 𝐇𝐰𝐞). I usually really love the korean raw beef, with a firm chewy texture. They serve it here with slices of pear, which added a textoral crunch and I didnt enjoy it. I would prefer having it on its own.

I also enjoyed the 𝐇𝐚𝐧𝐚𝐭𝐨𝐦𝐨𝐞 𝐘𝐨𝐝𝐚𝐧, with notes of ripe mango, jackfruit, banana and miso. While this look like the usual sake, it is anything but! Every sip brought out something different.

𝐓𝐫𝐞𝐞 𝐇𝐮𝐠𝐠𝐞𝐫 is cryptically named, but essentially plant-based hamburg with rice. I was shooked on first bite. How can this taste better than meat? Heck, even the texture was like meat. The charred leak gravy brought out extra flavour from the patty.

𝐑𝐢𝐜𝐞 𝐑𝐢𝐜𝐞 𝐑𝐢𝐜𝐞! was their take on local tao huey, but made from toasted rice. Quite fitting as sake is also made from rice. There was a savouriness in the dessert, making it quite multi-dimensional.

Back in 2018, in my many failed attempts to recreate Bundt’s iconic black cocoa brownies so I wouldn’t have to burn a hole in my wallet (though I think I ended up spending way more on my experimentations LOL), I fell in love!! with baking. ['📍: Hello Arigato

🚇: Upper Thomson 

•Hello Kombu Tots $12
This, like all tater tots, was crispy on the outside and soft on the inside. The accompanying sauce was tasty and added flavor to the dish. However, I thought it could be stronger because it was a little muted.

•Mentaiko Pasta $18
There's nothing special about this. The noodles were al dente, but the sauce was too jelak. The scallops were fresh, but the portion was small.

•Trule Portobello Sando $18
This was an outlet special, so I had to get it. As a mushroom fan, I had to get this. With the truffle mushroom jam and portobello mushroom, you can taste the mushroom but not the truffle flavor. Given that this "sandwich" costs $18, I wouldn't buy it again because it's very basic and not worth the price.

Everything was underwhelming and nothing stood out. My food experience does not appear to be as good as others', but this is most likely due to personal preference.

Jes/yy: The both of us LOOOVE anything matcha and were so excited and grateful when we were invited to @lilac.oak to try the new @naokimatcha.cafe oat latte!

〰️ 𝐍𝐚𝐨𝐤𝐢 𝐦𝐚𝐭𝐜𝐡𝐚 𝐨𝐚𝐭 𝐥𝐚𝐭𝐭𝐞 (𝐒$𝟕) - using Naoki Matcha’s Barista Blend, this matcha latte was extremely vibrant in colour, so just by sight, we could tell that it was going to be high-quality matcha 😍 We tried it both slightly sweetened and unsweetened, and preferred the slightly sweetened version as the syrup helped to cut through the bitter matcha but didn't overpower the taste of the matcha! The matcha latte itself had a very nice and rich flavour and was very well balanced, with just the right amount of milk 😋 They use oatly barista which is honestly my FAVOURITE plant milk to use with coffee/matcha bc its vv creamy and doesn't have an overpowering non-dairy milk taste 🤩 Would definitely recommend it to any matcha lover if you love a good, strong cup of matcha! 🍵

〰️ 𝐌𝐮𝐬𝐡𝐫𝐨𝐨𝐦 𝐓𝐨𝐟𝐮 𝐂𝐢𝐚𝐛𝐚𝐭𝐭𝐚 (𝐒$𝟗.𝟗𝟎) - With the lattes, we ordered the Mushroom Tofu Ciabatta for lunch! It came with a grilled tofu patty, mushrooms, housemade black bean dressing, crunchy vegetables, sandwiched between nicely toasted ciabatta. Jesmin REALLY liked this - it tasted simple and homely, yet somehow the combination of all the flavours just worked and rly rly hit the spot 😋😍 Our only qualm is that it was a bit small for the price, but nevertheless was really tasty and would get again! 

Oh also special mention that the staff were also so so friendly and attentive from the start, frequently checking if we needed anything - it really made us feel comfortable and welcome!! ☺️

荷叶药膳蒸熟鲍鱼全鸡

We were in awe when this came in! First of all, it was HUGE!!🔥🔥 We thought it could be shared within 4-5 people!!😳😳 AND, IT LOOKS SO GORGEOUS!!😍 So much like a treasure chest! The ‘treasures’ include abalone, herbs, mushrooms... there are so many nutritious and beneficial ingredients used to build up this dish🤤

Loved that the gravy is pretty well balanced, savoury and the herbal taste isn’t too strong. Since the chicken was wrapped inside the lotus leaves during the cooking process, it traps the natural sweet flavours and essences of the chicken! This made the chicken extra tender and well seasoned.🍗

Take note that this is only available for reservations as it takes at least 1 day to complete the dish😱

I would actually come back again for this dish!!🤍

Tmr is Mother’s Day, 👩‍🍼which brings me back a memory I had when I was younger! My mom would never fail to buy me Porridge when I was sick, and now, porridge has become my comfort food. And hearing that this porridge is traditionally made, I was super excited to try!🥰

This bowl was loaded with flavours, yet super comforting! The texture was super silky and smooth too☺️☺️💘

I was also surprised to hear that there was NO SOYA SAUCE ADDED at all!😮And the flavours came purely from the porridge, (ingredients such as handmade meatballs and watercress added so much flavours!!) through hand-stirred from scratch daily to achieve that silky texture!!

If you stay nearby this is definitely a choice for you to try whenever you crave for something simple yet yummy!

Address: BGAIN261 Eating House, BLK 261 Waterloo Street, #01-29, S180261

Opening Hours: Tuesday-Sunday 3pm-12am 

Review: I had this for dinner last night and I was really impressed by the quality of food! There aren’t many good zhi char spots in Singapore but I would definitely recommend this spot for it’s value and quality.

👉🏻Chilli Crab & Pepper crab ($19.90 special promo)
Both the crab dishes were very fresh, I particularly liked the chilli crab because it was spicy enough and yet still sweet and tangy at the same time. Also, the lala inside was also a nice addition and soaked up a lot of flavour from the sauce. 

👉🏻Prawn paste chicken ($12/$18)
The chicken wings were crispy and tender which basically hits the spot for har cheong gai! The prawn paste aroma is quite strong and we found it super addictive.

👉🏻Fish Steamboat ($15 special promo/$28 regular price)
The steamboat came in a charcoal pot which kept the dish piping hot throughout our meal. The fish was tender and the soup was really tasty with no fishy taste! I really liked the chilli that came along as it was garlicky and tangy which paired very well the fish slices. We were told that they purchased their fish fresh from the market every morning and you can add on pomfret or red snapper to “zhng” (improve) your dish! 

👉🏻Lemon grass pork ribs ($15/$20)
The pork ribs were quite tender and well seaonsed with a strong lemon grass taste. It is quite similar to korean fried chicken but with some thai elements to it! 

Overall: Kwan’s a super solid zhi char stall located in Bugis/Bras Basah area! The dishes are all super high quality and I would definitely recommend this to my friends!

Thank you for the invite @kwanszichar ! We enjoyed ourselves very much!🐷', '[Fatty Cheong] ($8.50)

Overall, i would probably go back again to try it fresh in the afternoon.

Rating: 6.5/10', '[Choon Kee Roasted Delights] ($4)

Opening Hours: 10.30am to 3pm daily, closed on Wednesday.

Address: 505 Beach Road #01-74, Golden Mile Food Centre, Singapore 199583

Review: This is one of the hidden gems that I’ve discovered recently and I really love it! I had this at lunch today and i actually cut the shao rou myself which explains the even sizes HAHA🐷 Extra tip here is to try dabaoing your shao rou and eating it with english mustard- the mustard really cuts through the fats and elevates the taste!!

I had shao rou char shao and shao ya - And I think that the most outstanding one is definitely the char shao. It was super sweet and fatty which a light char making it really impeccable. The shao rou and shao ya were also quite decent and the duck skin was especially fragrant. 

Overall, quite a suprising discovery at Golden Mile FC aka Army Market. The next I’m there, I’ll definitely struggle choosing between this and the hokkien mee/chicken rice/burger which are all excellent options😤

Rating: 8/10', '[碳烤黑叉烧] ($4.20)

448 Clementi Avenue 3 Singapore 120448 #01-15

Short Review- I think the char siew is pretty good but nothing amazing - they were also quite stingy on the portion and I ran out of meat before I finished the rice. 

Overall, I think it’s quite pricey at $4.20 for only char shao so I wouldn’t eat it again. However, I would act recommend their noodles instead because iirc, their noodles and wanton are actually pretty good so my take is to buy the noodles > rice 🐷.

📈:5/10', '📍120 Bukit Merah Lane 1, #01-27 Alexandra Village Food Centre, Singapore 150123

Opening Hours: Mon-Sun 8.30am-2.30pm, closed Wed & Thurs

Review: I had this stall last sunday at Alexandra Food Village. I actually intended to have Lau Phua Chay a pretty popular stall which is often featured in articles but I was intrigued by this stall due to the long queue. I told myself why not and proceeded to queue for it 😤. I actually planned to have rice but when i reached the front of the queue i saw a sign that said that they ran out of rice and I had to get noodles instead 😭.

Before I go in depth, I just wanna preface that the tldr is that the store was actually disappointing and that I wouldn’t go back for it again. First, the two roasted meat were quite average and nothing to get excited over. The char shao was a bit tough and there was no char or sweetness to it while the shao rou was not very crispy. While the shao rou was quite fatty, it was not crispy and tasted quite flat. 

Noodles + chilli - the noodles itself was also not very special. It had no flavour and tasted quite plain which did help the dish at all. The chilli was very normal and there’s nothing much to describe about it.

Overall, I was quite disappointed because i queued around 30 mins and tbvh I think that any random store around my neighbourhood would probably taste better than this.

📈: 3/10', '[华鸡同鸭讲港式烧腊] ($4)

📍 269 Queen Street #01-237, 180269 Singapore

Opening Hours: Mon - Sun 10:00 AM - 8:00 PM

This review is on one of my fav stalls in Singapore! It’s one of the og stalls that made me create this insta acc 😤 It’s quite an unassuming stall opposite the 四马路 temple and along the same stretch as the famous Rong Liang cssr. I rly love this stall and there was one week last year where I ate here 4 times in one week!

Back to the review proper: This stall can actually be quite inconsistent at times, somethings the char siew is too fatty and other times, the shao rou is not crispy. But most of the time, the hack is to order their 三宝饭 for $5 so you can all three roasted meats (shao rou, char shao and shao ya).

On the good days, all three can be super on point! Firstly, the shao rou will be crispy and fatty. Secondly, the char shao will be caramelize and charred perfectly. Lastly, the shao ya will be fatty with a light crispy skin😋

Rice and chilli- normally the rice is quite normal and nothing to rave about. But the chilli on the other hand is pretty good, it’s the garlic and lime chilli which helps to cut through the jelakness of the roasted meat. 

Overall, this is one of more underrated stalls in Singapore that no one really knows I feel🐷 TBVH, I’ve been there a few times last week but they were closed both times and I’m abit worried that they are closed for good haha😭 If it really is closed then this shall be my parting post \U0001f972

📈: rating: 8.5/10', '[Char Siu Lang]($5)

📍 Jalan Bukit Merah, #01-5134 Blk 2, Singapore 150002

Opening Hours: Mon-Sun 11am-6.30pm, closed on Wed

Review: This stall is quite hyped on the internet and has a pretty good story (owner won 1M lottery💸a few years back and decided to full time cssr instead). I went on a Sunday afternoon around 12pm where there was a short queue. I actually order 三拼饭 (SPF) instead of my normal cssr because I wanted to try the duck as well but to my surprise, they only served chicken🐓instead of duck.

Roasted meats- I think the roasted meats were slightly below my expectations😣. The chicken was quite tender but nothing out of the world. I actually ordered 半肥 for my char siew because I liked it slight more fatty. I think one thing quite commendable was that all the pieces given were actually perfectly balanced with a good ratio of fat to meat🤩. However, while the ratio was good, I did not find the char siew to be exception! There was no strong char flavour and it was not also super tender. While fatty, the fats were not really rendered and did not melt in my mouth. Lastly, the Shao Rou decent with a good crunch but had no x-factor- it was not super fragrant or crunchy.🤭

Rice + Chilli- I think one positive note is that the rice and chilli here was really good. The rice was chicken rice and was perfectly cooked. While many cssr places ignore their rice, I could tell that this place really put effort into their rice. Lastly, the chilli here was nice - tangy and sour']

['🧇 ANN CHIN POPIAH

One fine afternoon, I had to buy my fast-growing didi his first dinosaur phone so I stopped by Sim Lim Square. Though tbh he was just an excuse to go out of my way to try @annchinpopiah ’s WAFFLES.

Don’t be fooled by this popiah stall, because it’s actually an all-in-one powerhouse. Went straight for my usual go-to PB waffle, but then spotted the Godzilla-sized fried chicken waffles on the menu for $4.90 (it’s not Yard Bird ok). Auntie said “HEN HAO CHI DE” (very nice one) and I was VERY TEMPTATED cos she was so earnest. So I got both. 

No regrets, folks. Auntie happily served the waffles to me in brown open-top paper boxes, lovingly sliced into half. I hold the chunky chicken cutlet in between two halves of a waffle, still hot and crispy from the iron. The first bite is a flavour explosion: chicken juices, bbq sauce, nacho cheese, mayo, and slivers of tuckshop-tasting lettuce. They’re all wrapped up in the crispy, warm waffle sweetness that tapers off to a quasi-sogginess because the porous pancake has soaked up all the delish juices. Omg. I’m giddy with joy, oozey PB quadrant in one hand, finger-lickin-good chicken quadrant in the other, taking one bite out of each hand in turn. An intoxicating experience.

Tips: Go for their fillings. Give their popiahs a shot too because Ann Chin is a popiah connoisseur. I’m no expert in that realm but I LOVED it. Will be back to try the other offerings.

4/5. I do prefer my waffles kueh and dense-like, but this is 100% comfort food and perfect for those of you who enjoy it light and crispy. What brings me back to Ann Chin will be the ambience and service, and the simple thrill of warm lovingly-prepared food that you get from tuckshops and canteens of old schools and army camps. The interior is orange and cheery, it wasn’t too overcrowded around 4PM, and I had a couple of other customers for quiet chatter and company. The aunties were the cutest friendliest people. They were laughing at me as I was waving the waffle around in the air and taking pictures of it right in front of them. Vibes are immaculate. Now you no longer have to go to Sim Lim to buy/sell/repair electronics, just go for Ann Chin.', '🧇 YI JIA BAKERY HOUSE CAFE

I think my footage really speaks for itself in this one. A pandan waffle reimagined as an atas Belgian waffle, except served on kopitiam plastic plates and disposable cutlery. Probably the most affordable bakery cafe in town — a sit-down affair with neighbourhood bread store prices. Big plus for down-to-earth heartlander vibes. 

I might’ve shed some excited tears carving my plastic fork and knife through a warm bubbly pool of lip-smacking peanut butter decadence, slathered between two mochi-like waffle patties. Crispy on the outside and chewy on the inside (and you can definitely ask for more crispy if you swing that way). PERFECTLY BALANCED in all faculties. If you think it can’t get any better, they also sell FANTASTIC breads, some of the fluffiest doughs and most packed fillings I’ve ever eaten. 

Highly recommend for a go-to homely and cosy breakfast/ afternoon tea fix, with more comfortable seating than sweltering kopitiams but without the preppy-ness of cafes.

4/5. It was a glorious morning. Top notch in Upper Thomson, you really don’t need Salted Caramel. Will be back for more.', '🧇 DJ BAKERY (THOMSON PLAZA)

Spotted this tastY miSteR 😩😩 from afar because the batter pot was SO GREEN. ✅ Sweetness was just nice, not too sweet. The waffle is very light on the palate, which makes it not jelak. They seem v proud of having no additives! Humble and satisfying, feel-good tuck shop nostalgia vibes
✅ Plain is very affordable at $1.20! Filling price is not the cheapest but cheaper than Boleh and Bakery Cuisine']

Lastly, the seasalt, caramel and honeycomb didnt stand out and felt lacklustre to me 😔', "Fettucine with Cobble Lane Cured Nduja, Mascarpone & Lemon - £7.5

📍Padella│Southwark

Back at it again!! Finally able to eat out after a long lockdown. The first thing I decided to do was to eat some yummy pasta 🤤🤤 if you ever do visit Padella, make sure to be there early as they have a 1.5 hr eating time for the 4 tables (2 seats each) they have. 

I absolutely loved the tagliarini with crab 🦀 the lemon added a refreshing taste to umami from the seafood. Compared to the crab tagliarini, the fettucine with nduja was underwhelming. It tasted like a creamy spicy pasta with slight hints of porky flavour. Maybe its because i haven't had nduja before and that im a sucker for seafood? 😂
I decided to order a rosemary lemonade to complement the sunny day, and boy did it smack 😚😚😚 it rly was the perfect drink for summer! Sweet and sour lemonade with hints of evergreen, citrusy rosemary made a flawless combination 🤭 i loved it so much that i even went home to make it myself, but sadly it couldn't compare to the one i got from Padella 😬

Padella is defo the place to go for cheap, affordable pastas, but their prices have increased since pre-lockdown. They are still relatively cheaper than other pasta shops with decent portion sizes + there is Borough Market next to it to stuff yourself even more !!! 
Keep an eye out for more Borough Market posts to come 💯", "nothing to post because nothing is open and takeaway is expensive 😢 so here's a throwback to my avo toast 🥑

['Okay finally got off my procrastinating ass and typed this.
I always thought of myself as a rice vs pasta kind of person. However, this particular pasta changed my mind.
Standing at $26, this tagliatelle was the embodiment of perfection. Every mouth consisted of perfectly cooked pasta with a spring in each bite. I simply could not get enough. For the first time in a long time, the star of the show was truly the tagliatelle, not the sauce nor the meat - which faded into the background. Hell, if heaven was a thing, i would still pay for it. 
Moral of the story: I’m simply a carbs person. 🤷🏻‍♀️
~~~ 
Honorable mentions:
- Burrata was good & when eaten with the olive oil, a pinch of vinaigrette and nutty rocket, it was simply 👩‍🍳💋. 
- Their grilled lamb was really good too. Not gamy and the meat simply glides off the bone. 
- While the chocolate lava cake initially disappointed me with the ooze (or lack thereof), it made up for it with the taste. The charred and slightly bitter cake complemented the sweet vanilla ice cream really well.', '@apiary.sg ice cream is so smooth and criminal that i went twice in one month.

First time, i got their bailey’s & brownies ($4.70) flavor. There were a fair bit of chunky (just how i like it) brownies and i could definitely taste the bailey though not that strong, but I ain’t complaining. Did found the portion quite small could be probably cos i was hungry haha. 
~~
Second time, i tried their lavender ($4.20) and mugi cha (roasted barley tea ~ $4.70 cos premium) with waffles. This time round, the 2 scoops of ice cream were enough for 3. Maybe the takeaway cup too small 🤔

~~
Nonetheless, would most definitely go back to try the rest of their flavors!', 'Tried Havla for the first time and overall everything were pretty good. 
Genmaicha latte ($5.80) was by far the most enjoyable and i would most definitely order again. As a person whose nickname is commonly known as ”饭桶”, i naturally gravitated towards this drink. Side note, their decor reminds me of a sauna with the pebbles. Really pretty and chill place.', '#tgif
Featuring my cute ass pineapple rings 🍍🍍', 'Long overdue post but i’ve been making kimchi fried rice so often recently. Hands down the best way to get rid of overnight rice. If you don’t agree well you and me can have a very serious conversation... 
Recipe👇🏼
- Heat up some cooking oil & add minced garlic & fry for awhile 
- Fry the mushrooms (i used portobello mushrooms cos it has a meatier texture & also enoki) etc. (ie. basically things that take longer to cook like meats)
- Add the kimchi and fry till it’s softer but not totally cooked through
- Add the kimchi juice, followed by the rice & the sauce 
- Mix them well together (i also like to add a little water at this point so it wouldn’t be too dry) 
- Switch off the fire and let it set in the pan for abt a minute
- Finally fry an egg if you would like (you can use sesame oil to fry it for an extra oomph or drizzle sesame oil onto the rice after it’s cooked) 
- Top with roasted sesame seeds & laver to enjoy 😉

*Kimchi fried rice sauce (for 2 servings): 
- 1 tbsp gochujang, 1/2-1 tsp rice vinegar, 2 tbsp kimchi juice (if you don’t have enough can add a little more water & more gochujang instead), 1/2 tsp water 
(for the vinegar it’s dependent on how sour or ripened your kimchi already is & your preference) 
Do tag me if you ever try the recipe! 🙆🏻‍♀️🙆🏻‍♀️', 'Been a hectic week but i finally got around making myself breakfast.

#friedchicken #chickenwings #coconutrice #gluttony #spoonfeed #sgfood #sgigfoodies #sgigfood #sgig #exploresingapore #burrplesg #sgeats #sgfoodporn #instafood_sg #foodiefeature @singaporefoodlisting #exploresingaporeeats #foodsofig #eatmoresg', 'After trying a couple of their desserts, their nasi lemak was my favorite. Really sad to hear that tomorrow would be their last day! 🙁 
Everything about the “Nasi Lemak” dessert ($14.90) was created with thoughtfulness and creativity. From the slightly sweet and spicy “sambal chilli” which could have easily resembled the real thing, to their acidic “egg yolk” sorbet that complemented beautifully with the pandan mouuse which was covered with coconut. This dessert was the highlight of my day and it certainly did not hurt that it was gorgeous to look at 👀 
However, their “Roasted Oolong Pear” ($13.90) fell a little short for me. Although the pear was roasted quite well, the ice cream at the bottom was no longer as cold - probably from the pear directly on the top. This then hampered the wonderful contrast of cold vs hot that i was looking forward to. Taste wise, there was nothing very spectacular about chocolate in pear with ice-cream. 
The last dessert I tried was the “Chocolate Avalanche” ($13.90). It was really good with the chocolate lava cake truly molten and devilishly chocolate-ty. Sadly, the chocolate to ice cream ratio was not as expected as the delightful orange-infused (could really taste it) vanilla ice cream was gone in a couple of bites...

Finally tried the famous Dona Manis’s old-school, traditional banana pie that everyone’s been raving about...and can we just say we were absolutely blown away by this😍🤯 

Each slice was hefty, encasing a thick layer of moist, gooey sweet banana core that melts in your mouth, complete with a fragrant, buttery flaky crust that had lovely notes of coconut, topped off with crisp roasted almonds that not only added the addictive crunch factor, but further elevated the flavor. 🌿We absolutely loved the prominent osmanthus fragrance from the osmanthus jelly, along with the lovely textures in this beauty collagen dessert: the firm, chewy peach gum chunks with their addictive QQ jelly-like consistency, the melt-in-your-mouth soft pieces of gum tragacanth and osmanthus jelly, alongside the textural contrast from pieces of longan, wolf berries, ginkgo nuts and red dates! This has to be the omelette sandwich of our dreams🤩 I mean, have you ever seen an omelette sandwich with an omelette THIS thick and fluffy?!! 

Sandwiched between two delicious chewy slices of buttered toasted bread, this thick, fluffy Japanese omelette was also sweet-tasting, soft and chewy with a slightly runny core. Just the way we like it. 

We absolutely loved the 𝐓𝐚𝐦𝐚𝐠𝐨 𝐒𝐚𝐧𝐝𝐨, which had strong notes of dashi from the Kombu Mayo and made even more addictive than it already was with bonito flakes. A very authentic Japanese-style sandwich we just couldn’t get enough of. The 𝐒𝐩𝐚𝐦 𝐒𝐚𝐧𝐝𝐨 on the other hand got rather cloying after a while due to the overpowering Sriracha Mayo, which they could consider using less of. The thick layer of spam was good though, and this sando would satisfy those who like their sandwiches with meat and with stronger flavors. 

We’re definitely not exaggerating when we say this is the BEST tamago (japanese omelette) sandwich we’ve ever had in our lives.

💸💸💸(broke!)', 'It was the last 2 days of Melbourne brunch festival held in Singapore for the month of July! We visited Symmetry cafe @symmetrysg for their Melbourne brunch festival menu which uses Australian produce and here’s what we tried:

Eggs Benedict:
Part of their regular menu, their signature eggs benedict was everything an eggs benedict lover could ask for. Juicy poached egg slathered generously with creamy hollandoise sauce topped with bacon bits, melted cheese and mushrooms atop crisp toast, this was a feast for the eyes and mouth. The best part is the eggs ben wasn’t cloying like most and you can devour this easily within seconds. 

Triple Cream Brie toastie:
Thick slab of brie cheese topped with mushrooms and cream, sandwiched between two crisp slices of toast. As a cheese lover we enjoyed this but did prefer if the mushroom taste was less overpowering. Really loved the sweet tomato relish on the side which served as a dip for both the addictive tater tops and the toast. 

Steak and Eggs: 
Succulent chewy wagyu steak slices paired with guacamole and runny scrambled eggs, complete with a tinge of spice reminiscent of mediterranean flavors? Yes please. A combination we wouldn’t have expected could be this good. Finish that off with tasty roasted brussels sprouts and crisp addictive tater tots and you have a hearty meal and a very satisfied stomach. 

It’s not always that we can find cafes with great food, and Symmetry cafe is definitely one of the rare ones with great cafe food standard. Check it out soon if you haven’t already!', '🥓 fragrance bak kwa @fragrance_bak_kwa

What’s your favorite Western food catering? Ours has to be @craftandfood 🙌🏻

Only premium quality meats and ingredients are used here, and you can definitely taste the excellent quality and the effort Chef Danny puts into every dish, which he sells at value-for-money price points. Thick, juicy, tender and meaty, this was aromatic and loaded with flavor, complete with smoky undertones. Dip a slice of the beautifully charred beef into Chef Danny’s signature homemade “Secret Sauce” - a creamy, nutty, garlicky mixture - and it’s truly heaven in every bite. A must-order for meat lovers. 

𝗣𝗼𝗿𝗸 𝗖𝗼𝗹𝗹𝗮𝗿 ($50)

𝗧𝗮𝗯𝗯𝗼𝘂𝗹𝗲𝗵 & 𝗥𝗼𝗮𝘀𝘁𝗲𝗱 𝗖𝗮𝘂𝗹𝗶𝗳𝗹𝗼𝘄𝗲𝗿 (sides)

The tabbouleh was reminiscent of Middle Eastern flavors with its zingy, refreshing, spiced flavors that we just could not get enough of. 𝗠𝗶𝗻𝗶 𝗖𝗮𝗻𝗲𝗹𝗲𝘀 ($24 for ~20-30pcs)

𝘴𝘵𝘳𝘢𝘸𝘣𝘦𝘳𝘳𝘺 𝘴𝘢𝘯𝘥𝘰 omg i used to eat this back in korea however this one fell pretty flat. the strawberry wasn’t sweet but they tried to compensate it by using a sweeter cream. i didn’t really like that as it felt too unnaturally sweet and i would prefer the sweetness to come from the fruit itself. however, the bread was absolutely divine, soft and chewy how japanese bread should be. so disappointing but maybe now that it is strawberry season, they will be sweeter', 'MONT by @lees_confectionery

["SPO RECAP, REFLECTIONS. #powerliftingsingapore #powerliftingsg

Finished off SPO with 8/9 successful attempts (3 each for the Squat, Bench & Deadlifts). 

The past months of training was not the smoothest sailing although I had the BEST conditions to have a good prep in the run-up to SPO & although I did win this meet, it was totally under the expectations i've envisioned but my mental game was always up there & i know would never fail me.\xa0 

Starting off with my squat, my last warmup was 200kg before my first attempt of 210, second attempt of 220 & 3rd attempt of 225. Frankly didn't feel good from my last warmup of squat of 200kg and underperformed for this lift as I had squatted more in training. 

Went 3/3 successful attempts with bench at 117.5kg as my first bench attempt, 120 for the second & 122.5 for the 3rd, increasing my bench pr by 2.5kg. 

Went 2/3 successful attempts for deadlifts with a successful 225kg on the first attempt, no lift for my second attempt of 230kg due to a torn callus (2nd photo) which caused my grip to slip before the down command & a successful last attempt of 235kg, also underperformed this lift as I've deadlifted more in the gym. 

And failing the 2nd deadlift really caught me off guard as I've done that weight countless times, even so with my 3rd deadlift attempt, but i knew what I had do to & I know if I had to grind my last attempt, that is what I'll do & honestly what I take away from this meet is to roll with the punches when it comes. Severely underperformed this meet but i'll be stronger than ever next year, that I'm extremely sure of. 

Thanks to @marcusdsk , @matthewyapzr & @fatty.traininglog for making me feel like a king, always being served during the meet 😂 

Finished with a 582.5kg total. 

Upwards from here.

Squat 190/200/213x (Gold)

During my warm ups, squats felt great. First attempt of 190 didn't move too fast but i didn't allow that get into my head. Second attempt of 200kg felt a little slow and i knew if i wanted the Asian Record of 213kg i would have to fight and i know i am always ready for one. During the attempt for the Asian record coming out of the hole it was fast, then i was stuck for a little second, then it moved a little before the bar rolled over my head and did a little gym****ery. I was so so close to getting an AR in my last year as a sub-jr but i failed to. It was not a very good start but i knew i had bench & deadlifts later on and i couldn't let that affect me. Go to the 4th video for my 3rd attempt squat. (Be sure to watch it😂)
-
Bench 100/105/110 (Gold)

Leading up to the comp my bench was complete shit. Every time i bench it always felt hard.Warmups before my first attempt didnt feel light either. I think one of the takeaways is that i'm glad @marcusdsk gave me different bench variations in my programme which helped me to overload and get used to heavy benching. I was very surprised and satisfied with my bench as 110kg was what i could have done with a slingshot only. -

Deadlifts 215/227.5/235x (Gold)

Similar to squat, deadlift warmup didnt feel good. Groove was abit off on that day during warmups. First attempt wasn't as fast as i wanted it to be. Second attempt was better infact. I thought i had the third attempt as it was a conservative 7.5kg jump. It got off the ground, i got stuck a little then it budged then i got stuck again. I held it on for as long as i could but it didnt move. 
Total 537.5 (Gold)

Ended off this meet as the Asian Champion. I am very grateful to have the best of the best people in my team and i've no doubt about it that they're the best people for the job. @marcusdsk @fatty.traininglog @xmyzr @farhannafariddd

Not the typical bubble tea shop, Yi Fang specialize in fresh fruit tea and uses organic milk while achieving authentic Taiwanese premium tea.

\U0001f9cb𝐘𝐚𝐤𝐮𝐥𝐭 𝐏𝐞𝐚𝐜𝐡 𝐆𝐫𝐞𝐞𝐧 𝐓𝐞𝐚 - $𝟕.𝟑𝟎

\U0001f9cb𝐋𝐲𝐜𝐡𝐞𝐞 𝐅𝐫𝐮𝐢𝐭 𝐓𝐞𝐚 - $𝟔.𝟓𝟎

📍genius central
i’ve always had the impression that this place only sold healthy food which isn’t rly my kinda thing 🤡 but was pleasantly surprised by the variety of dishes served here! the mexican cheese quesadilla we got was served with crispy potato chunks and an array of sauces. the quesadilla itself was full of flavour with a generous serving of cheese inside, giving it that chewy, pleasant texture. we added organic chicken to the quesadilla, which was well-seasoned, albeit being slightly tough (cant expect too much from chicken breast though). the sides of potato chunks were crispy and seasoned well w salt and pepper, a simple but definitely welcomed addition to the dish. overall a rly nice play w a rly pleasant environment to dine in and even study! (when we went there were a lot of ppl studying or doing their work) do note that this place offers the burpple 1-1 deal as well for that added value-for-money 🤩
.
7/10 ⭐️

finally got to try this ice cream and waffles place which i’ve seen so often on burpple!! they have such an interesting variety of ice cream and waffles combinations, albeit being slightly pricey. we got the s’mores waffle w popcorn butterscotch ice cream and the sassy fellow waffle w vanilla ice cream! the s’mores waffles had toasted marshmallows, graham crackers and whipped cream, while the sassy fellow waffle had bananas, walnuts and came w a maple syrup sauce. i must say that for the price of the desserts, they were slightly disappointing. there was nothing spectacular about the waffles n ice cream, and there wasn’t rly enough ice cream to go with the whole waffle. overall a pretty average experience, although the burpple deal did make it slightly more positive.

.
9/10 ⭐️

📍the social space @ kreta ayer 
second time coming to this place to hv their smoothie bowls!! went pretty safe on my last visit and tried the “tough nut” bowl but i decided to be a little more adventurous this time and tried the “the hulk” bowl, which is a blended combination of matcha, banana, spinach, avocado, mint, coconut milk and honey. the smoothie had a v smooth texture with good consistency, and is a rly refreshing snack which can be likened to an açai bowl. the bowls are topped up w extra fruits (kiwi and dragonfruit), with coconut flakes and granola, adding that extra bit of texture and flavour to the bowl. an interesting combination of ingredients and fruits but one that definitely did not disappoint!! however, we weren’t rly fans of the “berry berry good” bowl as it was a little sour, so if you’re like us u cld ask for an extra serving of honey to balance out the sourness of the berries:) do note that burpple offers a 1-1 deal so it’ll cost about $9.50 for a smoothie bowl and cup of homemade lemonade if u decide to use it!! 
.
7/10 ⭐️

didn’t know healthy food could taste so good! been wanting to try shake farm for the longest time ever and i finally got ard to trying it last week! the grandma’s roast which had a generous serving of chicken breast on a bed of creamy carrot purée, infused with a delicious onion gravy. the star of the dish was definitely the carrot purée which was light but rich at the same time, with just the right amount of herbs and spices incorporated into it. we also tried the blueberry protein pancakes which were dense and very thicc, with the generous amount of fruits adding a refreshing burst of natural sweetness to the dish. definitely an extremely healthy meal that tasted even better! p.s. shake farm is on burpple as well, and u can get a 20% discount off ur total bill if u redeem the deal:)

📍the assembly ground @ cineleisure 
came to this place thrice and ordered the same thing all three times!! 😙 the pizza dishes at the assembly ground are definitely one of the more unique ones i’ve seen in cafes! the american cheeseburger pizza is pretty much a flat version of a burger - with minced beef, cheddar cheese, bbq sauce and mayo as it’s toppings. meanwhile, the umami roasted chicken pizza was topped with marinated roasted chicken, umami dashi sauce and bonito flakes. the pizzas each have their own unique and distinct flavour, and needless to say, the ingredients definitely go together rly coherently to create an explosion of flavours with every bite 🤤 the crust of the pizza is rather unusual as well, and has the texture of a pastry/puff rather than the usual pizza dough. overall, a cafe with a really pleasant ambience and food that is of even better quality. pricing is everything you’d expect from a typical cafe, although this place is on burpple as well so do make use of the deal if u happen to pop by!!

finally got the chance to try unclemario’s peanut kapet’s 🥜 - crispy wafers with a generous filling of rich and creamy peanut butter! this snack is rly highly addictive and definitely tastes as gd as it looks 🤤😙 the wafer on the outside is crispy and has a light sweetness about it, reminding me of love letters that one eats during the CNY period. on the inside, the snack oozes with a decadent and abundance of peanut butter filling (u can choose other fillings as well!!). the slight saltiness and rich, heavy texture or the peanut butter does really well to complement the light crispy wafer on the outside. 🤝 while the deliciousness of the kapet is undebatable, the price tag is a little on the costly side, although for a freshly handmade product and with the amount of filling they provide this is pretty understandable! one down side is that unclemario only offers the delivery option ($8 💸💸) which may be slightly pricey esp if you’re only ordering 1 tub on its own. nevertheless, the kapet is a hearty snack that is sure to leave you satisfied, and even if this isn’t kind of treat, @unclemariosg does offer a wide variety of other traditional snacks that i’m sure are of similar quality!

📍Hawkers’ Street @ ION Orchard (beach road scissor cut curry rice & king of fried rice)
chanced upon this stall in the food street of ION and i must say it is q a novel concept! Hawkers’ Street is a combination of multiple famous hawker stalls and eateries from around sg, and features local delights such as hokkien mee, scissor cut curry rice and DTF-esque fried rice 😮‍💨😱 eventually we decided to order from the franchise of the famous beach road scissor cut curry rice and king of fried rice stalls:) was lucky enough to tried the food from the authentic stalls bfor trying these, and i was pleasantly surprised by how authentic the dishes tasted! 

scissor cut curry rice: 7/10 ⭐️
the scissor cut curry rice was drenched in a generous serving of their famous curry and black sauces, and the ingredients we got (pork cutlet, egg and ngor hiang) were flavourful and had a crispy texture 🤠 overall a very satisfying meal that definitely comes close to the original version from beach road. only down side to this was that it was a little on the pricey side ($7), although it’s still relatively affordable for a stall located in the heart of ion orchard!!

egg fried rice w pork cutlet: 7/10 ⭐️
the egg fried rice had a rly fragrant scent and was topped with a thick and crispy pork cutlet. this dish definitely resembles the egg fried rice dish at ding tai feng at first glance and you’ll be amazed at how similar it tastes as well!! the star of the dish was undoubtedly the egg fried rice, which was well-fried with a generous portion of eggs and spring onion that contribute to the texture and fragrance of the rice. the pork cutlet was crispy on the outside and relatively well-seasoned, although it is a little on the dry side and not as juicy as i’d hoped for it to be 😔 nevertheless it is definitively worth a try if you are craving the egg fried rice from DTF but for half the price!! 
.

Milksha is popular for its fresh milk series and the fresh taro milk is one of their best sellers! In March, they launched their taro balls topping, which is imported from Taiwan! 

I usually order tea with no milk/creamer but I had to give this a try because I’m a trash for taro 🥰.

Verdict? On my first sip, I was astounded by the sweetness of the taro paste but subsequently I thought it was not too sweet after giving my drink a stir. The taro balls topping paired really well with the drink, it was love at first sip for me 🤣.

As someone who doesnt drink fresh milk that frequently (I’m slightly lactose intolerant and not a fan of milky taste also), I was surprised that I actually really love this drink! The milk + taro paste were well balanced teeeheeee.

💯:🌸🌸🌸/5
💸: $24🥶
📍: five guys, plaza singapura 

My brother and I were taken aback by the prices of the food on the menu. The ala carte burger was $15, and the ala carte fries was $9.

When we ordered the cheeseburger, we were told that we could choose what we would like to have in the burger (e.g. onions, lettuce, tomatoes, sauce). There was no limit to it, which I was quite surprised to find out.

Taste wise, the beef was very juicy and tender and the cheese used was just nice and was overall very satisfying. It was a mess eating it though, as pieces of vegetables kept falling off but I guess that’s what makes it a great burger? 

Next up the fries 🍟! It was a generous portion of fries and i loved how the fries were done. It was pretty obvious that this weren’t the frozen ones, as I could tell that this was handmade. The inside of fries had the texture of mash potatoes, which were really nice. 
The fries are deep-fried in peanut oil which I wasn’t really a big fan of. The fries had this peanut smell which felt rather jelat after eating a few pieces.

Overall, I wouldn’t come back again for the burgers or fries but maybe I’ll be back for what they are known for- their milkshakes. 
It is really pricey, so prepare your wallets if you visit Five Guys. \U0001f972', '🍜🇯🇵

there are 3 types you can opt for; 

🥢tamago (2 slices chashu, 1 whole tamago)
🥢chashu (4 slices chashu)
🥢special (2 slices chashu, half tamago, seaweed)!

They are priced differently but I really love that they allow customers to choose what they’d prefer to have their ramen with! (you get to choose the doneness of the noodles too🥳)

I’ve to say this is one of the best ramen I had in Singapore. (Maybe I haven’t tried ENOUGH)

At other ramen places, I didn’t like that it was already salty when I take my first bite. When I had my first taste, it was not sickeningly salty! I enjoyed the rich tonkotsu broth and the noodles, which were perfectly cooked to my liking. 
As always, I think the egg was the best part!! It was so soft yet cooked perfectly just like an onsen egg 🥚 
However, the spicy miso that contained some chilli oil kinda overpowered the broth but I think they’ll be people that enjoy it😆

Totally would go back when I feel like giving myself a treat! Highly recommended to all 🥳🥰🤍', '\U0001f9cb🍓

I dare say this is the best oatmilk brand out there, and therefore too good to gatekeep!! 😩❤️

OATla is a relatively new store that popped up in Golden Mile Food Center, serving natural oatmilk with no added oils (unlike commercially produced ones) 😚 Spoke to the very friendly boss and he said the sweetness of the milk varies day to day because it's naturally made! 

Upon first sip, it reminded me so much of traditional soymilk but milder and creamier with an oatmeal aftertaste. Those who are not a fan of Oatly and other brands because of how "oaty" it tastes will like this! My bf agreed that it really tasted like tau huay zui hahaha. I ordered the 𝐆𝐚𝐫𝐥𝐢𝐜 𝐎𝐢𝐥 𝐓𝐨𝐧𝐤𝐨𝐭𝐬𝐮 𝐑𝐚𝐦𝐞𝐧 [~ $𝟕 𝐢𝐬𝐡]and topped up an egg for a dollar. It came with a singular char siew, black fungus and spring onions.

Rating: 6/10", "📍 Nice Rice

Helmed by an ex one Michelin star chef, Nice Rice specialises in French-Japanese inspired rice bowls! I had the 𝐒𝐡𝐫𝐨𝐨𝐦 𝐁𝐨𝐰𝐥 [$𝟕] which consisted of roasted mushrooms, mushroom glaze, garlic confit and a slice of roasted eggplant all on a bed of truffle-y, slightly buttery rice.

Rating: 10/10", "Matcha mornings has recently been looking super pretty with this easy Strawberry Matcha Latte ❤️

Ingredients: 
- 3 strawberries, diced into small chunks and slightly mashed
- 200ml milk of your choice (I used VitaSoy here) 
- 4 tbs warm water
- 2 tsp matcha powder @naokimatcha 
- Ice

1. Add the strawberries into the cup
2. Dissolve the matcha in 4 tbs warm water and whisk till foamy 
3. Add the milk into your cup
4. Layer the matcha mixture on top

The Superior Blend from Naoki Matcha checks off all the boxes - distinct umami with a hint of bitterness. As a hardcore matcha lover, I thoroughly enjoyed the earthy profile and the vibrant green 🥺❤️ A huge plus point for me is that it is really easy to dissolve as well!

The tartness of the strawberries surprisingly goes well with the bitterness of the matcha, giving the matcha latte a very refreshing twist. Feel free to add a dollop of honey to sweeten it up! A big thank you to @naokimatcha for sending this over - i'm a huge fan ❤️ 

Naoki Matcha is available on Shopee so get yours here 🥰 >> http://shor.by/shp_naokimatcha_sup", "📍 Glacier

Hardly any café which serves mains warrants a second visit especially within a month - but there's something about Glacier's food and aesthetics that keeps me coming back. 😍

The eggs were poached perfectly but the hollandaise sauce overpowered the avocado by a little. Overall it's a wholesome dish that definitely will fill you up 👍 I still like the French Toast better from Glacier so be sure to try that out!!
